ormate/formaldehyde/formamide) and surface (atmospheric HCN photochemistry) environments. The network topology is strong: 18 molecules and 13 reactions with 5 well-connected hub molecules (HCN degree 4, NH\u2083 degree 5, H\u2082S degree 3, formate degree 3, formamide degree 3). Convergent pathways to HCN from two independent sources (atmospheric photochemistry and formamide decomposition) provide network robustness. The H\u2082S and NH\u2083 recycling loops correctly capture the autocatalytic features of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Literature alignment is excellent \u2014 all 5 core cyanosulfidic steps match Patel et al. 2015 precisely, with correct intermediates (4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile). Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_007 (formaldehyde \u2192 acrolein) is oversimplified and chemically questionable as a single step \u2014 this is the weakest link in the network; (2) elemental copper for rxn_011 is not represented as a molecule node; (3) rxn_013 stoichiometry should consume 2 H\u2082O; (4) the network claims to produce L-Proline but the cyanosulfidic pathway produces a racemic mixture \u2014 chirality is not addressed; (5) rxn_004 lacks mineral specification for a surface reaction. Despite these issues, the network demonstrates strong chemical reasoning, excellent literature alignment, and meaningful environmental interconnection.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.90,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.87\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.75, "rxn_007": 0.55, "rxn_008": 0.85, "rxn_009": 0.95, "rxn_010": 0.95, "rxn_011": 0.85, "rxn_012": 0.95, "rxn_013": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.78, "pathway_coherence": 0.82, "environmental_progression": 0.84, "target_achievement": 0.87, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "This full-length pathway faithfully implements the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulf