and atmospheric HCN synthesis (rxn_006) provide realistic feedstock generation. Main weaknesses: rxn_007 (formaldehyde to acrolein oversimplified), rxn_011 missing explicit Cu\u2070 agent, rxn_013 H\u2082O stoichiometry. Despite these, the overall pathway is scientifically sound and well-aligned with literature.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_004"], "suggestions": ["Decompose rxn_007 into formose-type aldol steps (CH2O \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acrolein)", "Add Cu\u2070 as an explicit agent/molecule node for rxn_011", "Fix stoichiometry of rxn_013 (2 H\u2082O consumed)", "Specify mineral catalyst for rxn_004", "Address chirality \u2014 the network produces racemic proline, not specifically L-Proline"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P10", "overall_confidence": 0.85, "network_feedback": "This is a well-constructed synthesis network that faithfully implements the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic proline synthesis as its core (rxn_009\u2013rxn_013), and extends it with plausible upstream feedstock generation in hydrothermal (CO\u2082 fixation to formate/formaldehyde/formamide) and surface (atmospheric HCN photochemistry) environments. The network topology is strong: 18 molecules and 13 reactions with 5 well-connected hub molecules (HCN degree 4, NH\u2083 degree 5, H\u2082S degree 3, formate degree 3, formamide degree 3). Convergent pathways to HCN from two independent sources (atmospheric photochemistry and formamide decomposition) provide network robustness. The H\u2082S and NH\u2083 recycling loops correctly capture the autocatalytic features of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Literature alignment is excellent \u2014 all 5 core cyanosulfidic steps match Patel et al. 2015 precisely, with correct intermediates (4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile). Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_007 (formaldehyde \u2192 acrolein) is oversimplified and chemically questionable as a single step \u2014 this is the weakest link in the network; (2) elemental copper for rxn_011 is not represented as a molecule node; (3) rxn_013 stoichiometry should consume 2 H\u2082O; (4) the network claims to produce L-Proline but the cyanosulfidic pathway produces a racemic mixture \u2014 chirality is not addressed; (5) rxn_004 lacks mineral specification for a surface reaction. Despite these issues, the network demonstrates strong chemical reasoning, excellent literature alignment, and meaningful environmental interconnection.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.9, "convergence_quality": 0.87}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 277539.1528606415, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-18T09:57:08.272588", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Proline: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nOne experimentally demonstrated pathway produces L-Proline (C5H9NO2, SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C(=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8), MW: 115.13) from prebiotically available precursors via cyanosulfidic chemistry in surface environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Pyrrolidine Route (Surface Environment)\n\nThis 5-step pathway builds the pyrrolidine ring of proline through a sequence of cyanohydrin formation, thiolation-cyclization, reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis. The entire chemistry was demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) as part of the cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework.\n\n**Step 1 \u2014 Cyanohydrin formation**: 3-aminopropanal + HCN \u2192 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\n- SMILES: NCCC=O.C#N>>N#CC(O)CCN\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation \u2014 hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03) undergoes nucleophilic addition to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal (C3H7NO, SMILES: C(CN)C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2, MW: 73.09). The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, forming a new C\u2013C bond and yielding the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: C(CN)C(C#N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2, MW: 100.12). The free amine group on the 3-aminopropanal is preserved for subsequent cyclization.\n\n**Step 2 \u2014 Thiolation and cyclization**: 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile + H\u2082S \u2192 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCN.S>>OC1CCNC1=S.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, H\u2082S atmosphere\n- Mechanism: Hydrogen sulfide (H2S, SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2, MW: 34.08) attacks the nitrile carbon of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, converting the C\u2261N group to a thioamide (C=S). The primary amine at the opposite end of the chain then undergoes intramolecular cyclization by attacking the thioamide carbon, forming the five-membered pyrrolidine ring. This produces 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione (C4H7NOS, SMILES: C1CNC(=S)C1O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7), MW: 117.17) with release of ammonia (NH3, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03). This step simultaneously achieves ring closure and introduces the thione functional group that is central to the subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations.\n\n**Step 3 \u2014 Reductive deoxygenation**: 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-thione + H\u2082O\n- SMILES: OC1CCNC1=S>>S=C1CCCN1.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H\u2082S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu], SMILES: [Cu])\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Mechanism: Reductive deoxygenation \u2014 the hydroxyl group at C3 of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione is removed with loss of water (H2O, SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2, MW: 18.01). Elemental copper acts as a reductant in concert with hydrogen sulfide. The Cu/H\u2082S system provides the reducing equivalents needed to cleave the C\u2013OH bond, yielding pyrrolidine-2-thione (C4H7NS, SMILES: C1CC(=S)NC1, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6), MW: 101.17). This step is critical for producing the fully reduced pyrrolidine ring needed for the final proline product.\n\n**Step 4 \u2014 Thione-to-nitrile exchange**: pyrrolidine-2-thione + HCN \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + H\u2082S\n- SMILES: S=C1CCCN1.C#N>>N#CC1CCCN1.S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, HCN present\n- Mechanism: The thione (C=S) group of pyrrolidine-2-thione is displaced by cyanide. HCN attacks the thioamide carbon, replacing the sulfur with a nitrile group. This thione-to-nitrile exchange releases H\u2082S and produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (C5H8N2, SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2, MW: 96.13). The released H\u2082S is recycled back into the cyanosulfidic network. This reaction converts the sulfur-containing heterocycle into a nitrile-bearing pyrrolidine that can undergo hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (proline).\n\n**Step 5 \u2014 Nitrile hydrolysis**: pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 L-Proline + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC1CCCN1.O.O>>N.O=C(O)C1CCCN1\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Mechanism: Hydrolysis of the nitrile group (C\u2261N) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon nucleophilically, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide), which undergoes a second hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed. The product is L-Proline (C5H9NO2, SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C(=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8), MW: 115.13), a cyclic (pyrrolidine-containing) amino acid.\n\nThis 5-step pathway is notable because it constructs the pyrrolidine ring \u2014 a structural feature unique to proline among the proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 through cyanosulfidic chemistry. The pathway showcases the role of H\u2082S and HCN as interconverting sulfur and nitrogen functional groups through thioamide and nitrile intermediates, a hallmark of the Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: C(CN)C(C#N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Key branch-point intermediate** \u2014 this aminonitrile cyanohydrin is the product of the Strecker-type addition of HCN to 3-aminopropanal. It contains both the free amine and nitrile groups required for the subsequent thiolation-cyclization step that forms the pyrrolidine ring. It is consumed by H\u2082S-mediated cyclization to produce 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n### Hub Molecule: pyrrolidine-2-thione (C4H7NS)\n- Formula: C4H7NS\n- SMILES: C1CC(=S)NC1\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 101.17\n- Role: **Central cyclic intermediate** \u2014 pyrrolidine-2-thione is the reduced pyrrolidine ring bearing a thione group. It is produced by reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione (using Cu/H\u2082S), and consumed by thione-to-nitrile exchange with HCN to produce pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This molecule sits at the junction between the ring-formation steps and the nitrile/hydrolysis steps that produce proline (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n### Hub Molecule: hydrogen cyanide (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: **Upstream hub \u2014 carbon and nitrogen source** \u2014 HCN participates in two distinct reactions in the network: (1) Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation with 3-aminopropanal (Step 1), and (2) thione-to-nitrile exchange with pyrrolidine-2-thione (Step 4). HCN is a prebiotically abundant molecule produced by atmospheric photochemistry (UV irradiation of N\u2082/CH\u2084/CO\u2082 mixtures), volcanic outgassing, and impact-generated synthesis.\n\n### Hub Molecule: hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S)\n- Formula: H2S\n- SMILES: S\n- InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\n- MW: 34.08\n- Role: **Recycled sulfur carrier** \u2014 H\u2082S is consumed in Step 2 (thiolation-cyclization) and regenerated in Step 4 (thione-to-nitrile exchange), creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. It also serves as a co-reductant with elemental copper in Step 3 (reductive deoxygenation). H\u2082S is prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing and hydrothermal vents.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**3-aminopropanal** (C3H7NO)\n- Formula: C3H7NO\n- SMILES: C(CN)C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\n- MW: 73.09\n- Role: Starting material \u2014 the C3 amino aldehyde that provides the carbon backbone and amine nitrogen for the pyrrolidine ring. 3-aminopropanal can form prebiotically from acrolein (propenal) + NH\u2083, or from Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein. It is produced in cyanosulfidic reaction networks from simple C1\u2013C3 feedstocks (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n**3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione** (C4H7NOS)\n- Formula: C4H7NOS\n- SMILES: C1CNC(=S)C1O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)\n- MW: 117.17\n- Role: First cyclic intermediate \u2014 formed by H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. Retains a hydroxyl group at C3 that is removed in the subsequent reductive deoxygenation step. This intermediate demonstrates the simultaneous ring closure and thione formation that is characteristic of cyanosulfidic pyrrolidine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n**pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile** (C5H8N2)\n- Formula: C5H8N2\n- SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\n- MW: 96.13\n- Role: Penultimate intermediate \u2014 the nitrile-bearing pyrrolidine produced by thione-to-nitrile exchange. Both the pyrrolidine ring and the C5 carbon skeleton are complete at this stage; only hydrolysis of the nitrile to a carboxylic acid remains to yield proline (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n**Ammonia** (NH\u2083)\n- Formula: H3N\n- SMILES: N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- MW: 17.03\n- Role: Byproduct released in Step 2 (cyclization) and Step 5 (nitrile hydrolysis). Prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing, atmospheric photochemistry, and hydrothermal systems. Recycled as nitrogen source for other prebiotic reactions.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H\u2082O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H\u2082S** (hydrogen sulfide): SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\n- **NH\u2083** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **3-aminopropanal**: SMILES: C(CN)C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reaction R1: Cyanohydrin formation (Strecker-type)\n- 3-aminopropanal + HCN \u2192 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\n- SMILES: NCCC=O.C#N>>N#CC(O)CCN\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal, forming the cyanohydrin (\u03b1-hydroxynitrile) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. This is the carbon\u2013carbon bond forming step that extends the C3 aldehyde to the C4 aminonitrile, setting up the chain length needed for pyrrolidine ring formation.\n\n### Reaction R2: Thiolation-cyclization\n- 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile + H\u2082S \u2192 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCN.S>>OC1CCNC1=S.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, H\u2082S atmosphere\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: H\u2082S attacks the nitrile carbon, converting C\u2261N to a thioamide (C=S). The terminal amine then performs intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the thioamide carbon, closing the five-membered pyrrolidine ring and releasing NH\u2083. This one-pot thiolation-cyclization is characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry, where H\u2082S activates nitriles toward cyclization.\n\n### Reaction R3: Reductive deoxygenation\n- 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-thione + H\u2082O\n- SMILES: OC1CCNC1=S>>S=C1CCCN1.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H\u2082S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu], SMILES: [Cu])\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Reductive removal of the C3 hydroxyl group. The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system donates electrons to cleave the C\u2013OH bond, producing the fully reduced pyrrolidine-2-thione with loss of water. Elemental copper is a plausible prebiotic reductant in cyanosulfidic scenarios \u2014 copper deposits are formed by reduction of dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a by H\u2082S in surface geochemical settings.\n\n### Reaction R4: Thione-to-nitrile exchange\n- pyrrolidine-2-thione + HCN \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + H\u2082S\n- SMILES: S=C1CCCN1.C#N>>N#CC1CCCN1.S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, HCN present\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Cyanide displaces the thione sulfur at C2 of the pyrrolidine ring. HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic thioamide carbon. The C=S bond is broken with release of H\u2082S, and a new C\u2013CN bond is formed, yielding the nitrile. This reaction converts a sulfur-containing functional group to a nitrogen-containing one \u2014 a key interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry. The released H\u2082S is recycled for use in Step 2 (thiolation-cyclization).\n\n### Reaction R5: Nitrile hydrolysis\n- pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 L-Proline + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC1CCCN1.O.O>>N.O=C(O)C1CCCN1\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Sequential hydrolysis of the nitrile group \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide), which undergoes further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed. This completes the conversion of the nitrile to the carboxylate, yielding L-Proline.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe following agents are experimentally documented for reactions in the L-Proline synthesis network:\n\n- **Elemental copper (Cu\u2070)**: Metallic copper (SMILES: [Cu]). Acts as a reductant in the Cu/H\u2082S system for the reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione to pyrrolidine-2-thione (Reaction R3). Elemental copper is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper deposits form when dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions are reduced by H\u2082S in geochemical settings. Copper is found in hydrothermal and surface environments associated with sulfide mineralization. Used in: reductive deoxygenation (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n- **Hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S)**: Sulfidic acid (SMILES: S). Dual role: (1) acts as a co-reductant with elemental copper in the reductive deoxygenation step (Reaction R3), and (2) serves as the sulfur source for thiolation-cyclization (Reaction R2) and is regenerated by thione-to-nitrile exchange (Reaction R4). H\u2082S is abundantly available from volcanic outgassing, hydrothermal vents, and sulfide mineral dissolution. Used in: thiolation-cyclization (Reaction R2) and reductive deoxygenation (Reaction R3).\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN, H\u2082S, and simple aldehydes that produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids under plausible prebiotic surface conditions. For proline specifically, this study established the complete 5-step pathway from 3-aminopropanal + HCN through a series of cyanosulfidic transformations: (1) cyanohydrin formation \u2192 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, (2) H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization \u2192 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione, (3) Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-thione, (4) HCN-driven thione-to-nitrile exchange \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and (5) nitrile hydrolysis \u2192 L-Proline. The pathway is notable for constructing the pyrrolidine ring \u2014 unique among proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 through cyanosulfidic ring closure rather than through conventional Strecker synthesis, which cannot form cyclic amino acids. The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system used in Step 3 demonstrates that prebiotically available metals and sulfur species can drive reductive transformations needed for amino acid synthesis. The recycling of H\u2082S (consumed in Step 2, regenerated in Step 4) exemplifies the catalytic sulfur cycling central to the cyanosulfidic framework.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary)\nAll five reactions in the L-Proline synthesis pathway operate under surface cyanosulfidic conditions:\n- **Evaporitic pools and geothermal surface settings**: The reactions occur at ambient temperature and pressure in aqueous solution, consistent with shallow surface pools near volcanic/geothermal sources where HCN and H\u2082S are delivered by outgassing.\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions**: The pathway requires co-availability of HCN and H\u2082S \u2014 conditions found at the interface of volcanic degassing zones and surface water bodies. UV irradiation (relevant for other cyanosulfidic transformations) may also play a role in generating or activating some of the feedstocks.\n- **Copper availability**: Elemental copper for the reductive deoxygenation step (Reaction R3) is prebiotically plausible in surface settings where dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions from weathered copper minerals are reduced by H\u2082S to deposit native copper.\n- **3-Aminopropanal production**: The starting material 3-aminopropanal is itself a product of cyanosulfidic/surface chemistry \u2014 it can form from acrolein (produced by formaldehyde condensation or thermal decomposition of glycerol) reacting with ammonia, or from reductive amination of malondialdehyde.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\n- **Surface \u2192 Biochemical**: L-Proline produced by this pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool. As a cyclic imino acid with a rigid pyrrolidine ring, proline introduces structural constraints (kinks and turns) into prebiotic peptides. Proline-containing peptides formed by wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces in the Biochemical environment would have distinct conformational properties compared to peptides composed only of linear amino acids.\n- **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Simple feedstock molecules (HCN, H\u2082S, NH\u2083, aldehydes) can be produced in hydrothermal environments and transported to surface pools via ocean circulation and volcanic outgassing, where they fuel the cyanosulfidic proline synthesis pathway.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **3-Aminopropanal availability**: The pathway begins with 3-aminopropanal, a reactive amino aldehyde whose prebiotic concentration and stability in surface pools is uncertain. As an aldehyde, it is susceptible to oxidation, polymerization, and reaction with other nucleophiles present in the prebiotic milieu. The flux of 3-aminopropanal production versus its consumption by competing reactions is a key constraint on this pathway.\n\n2. **Chirality**: The cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic proline (equal L and D). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-proline) is unresolved. Possible enantioselection mechanisms include asymmetric crystallization, chiral mineral surfaces, or amplification through autocatalytic cycles, but none has been definitively demonstrated for proline.\n\n3. **Copper availability and oxidation state**: The reductive deoxygenation step (Reaction R3) requires elemental copper (Cu\u2070). While native copper can form from Cu\u00b2\u207a reduction by H\u2082S, the steady-state concentration of Cu\u2070 in prebiotic surface environments is poorly constrained. Whether sufficient Cu\u2070 would persist in the presence of other oxidants and complexing agents is an open question.\n\n4. **Cyclic vs. linear amino acid selectivity**: The cyanosulfidic pathway is specific to cyclic amino acids (proline) because the cyclization step (Reaction R2) depends on the intramolecular distance between the amine and the thioamide. For 3-aminopropanal, this distance is exactly right for five-membered ring formation. Whether similar pathways could produce other ring sizes (e.g., pipecolic acid from 4-aminobutanal) is an interesting extension.\n\n5. **H\u2082S recycling efficiency**: The pathway features an elegant sulfur cycle where H\u2082S is consumed in Step 2 and regenerated in Step 4. However, the efficiency of this recycling under real prebiotic conditions \u2014 with H\u2082S loss to oxidation, mineral precipitation (as metal sulfides), and atmospheric escape \u2014 may limit the catalytic turnover.\n\n6. **Nitrile hydrolysis rate**: The final step (Reaction R5) requires hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to the carboxylic acid. Nitrile hydrolysis at ambient temperature and neutral pH can be slow (days to weeks). The kinetics of this step under realistic prebiotic conditions (variable pH, temperature fluctuations, presence of metal ions that could catalyze hydrolysis) need further characterization.\n\n7. **Yield and selectivity**: While Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated all the individual steps, the overall yield of proline through the complete 5-step sequence has not been reported for a one-pot continuous process. Side reactions at each step (particularly the competing intermolecular reactions of the aminonitrile intermediate) could reduce the net yield significantly.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-constructed synthesis network that faithfully implements the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic proline synthesis as its core (rxn_009\u2013rxn_013), and extends it with plausible upstream feedstock generation in hydrothermal (CO\u2082 fixation to formate/formaldehyde/formamide) and surface (atmospheric HCN photochemistry) environments. The network topology is strong: 18 molecules and 13 reactions with 5 well-connected hub molecules (HCN degree 4, NH\u2083 degree 5, H\u2082S degree 3, formate degree 3, formamide degree 3). Convergent pathways to HCN from two independent sources (atmospheric photochemistry and formamide decomposition) provide network robustness. The H\u2082S and NH\u2083 recycling loops correctly capture the autocatalytic features of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Literature alignment is excellent \u2014 all 5 core cyanosulfidic steps match Patel et al. 2015 precisely, with correct intermediates (4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile). Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_007 (formaldehyde \u2192 acrolein) is oversimplified and chemically questionable as a single step \u2014 this is the weakest link in the network; (2) elemental copper for rxn_011 is not represented as a molecule node; (3) rxn_013 stoichiometry should consume 2 H\u2082O; (4) the network claims to produce L-Proline but the cyanosulfidic pathway produces a racemic mixture \u2014 chirality is not addressed; (5) rxn_004 lacks mineral specification for a surface reaction. Despite these issues, the network demonstrates strong chemical reasoning, excellent literature alignment, and meaningful environmental interconnection.\n- Issues: ['Uses atmospheric UV photochemistry of N\u2082/CH\u2084 (well-established Titan-like chemistry) to supply HCN for the cyanohydrin step. Still depends on the problematic rxn_007 for acrolein/3-aminopropanal. This pathway only has 6 steps described but needs formaldehyde from somewhere \u2014 missing the explicit upstream source for 3-aminopropanal in this pathway description.', 'Routes through surface formate\u2013ammonia condensation. rxn_004 should specify a mineral catalyst for the surface condensation. The formate + NH\u2083 \u2192 formamide step is thermodynamically unfavorable without activation energy input or catalysis. Still contains the problematic rxn_007.', 'This is a partial pathway (3 steps) providing atmospheric HCN for the thione-to-nitrile exchange. It does not independently produce proline \u2014 it is a branch that feeds into the main pathway. As a standalone pathway it is incomplete.', \"Correctly identifies the H\u2082S catalytic sulfur cycle (consumed in rxn_010, regenerated in rxn_012) as described in Patel et al. 2015. This is an important feature of the cyanosulfidic framework. However, as a 'pathway' it is really a sub-cycle within the main pathway, not a route to the target.\", 'Correctly identifies ammonia recycling: NH\u2083 is consumed in rxn_008 (Michael addition) and regenerated in rxn_010 (cyclization) and rxn_013 (hydrolysis). This autocatalytic feedback is a genuine feature of the cyanosulfidic network. The pathway as described shows the nitrogen economy well.', 'A branch pathway supplying HCN from hydrothermal formamide for the thione-to-nitrile exchange step. Chemically sound but incomplete as a route to proline \u2014 only covers HCN supply and the last two transformations.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Proline (racemic, prebiotically produced)\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network implements the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline synthesis from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) as the core 5-step pathway, embedded within a broader prebiotic feedstock-generation network spanning hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. The core pathway converts 3-aminopropanal through cyanohydrin formation, H\u2082S-mediated thiolation-cyclization, Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis to yield proline. Upstream, hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on greigite/magnetite produces formate, formaldehyde, and acetaldehyde; formate condenses with NH\u2083 on mackinawite to yield formamide, which decomposes to HCN. Independently, atmospheric UV photochemistry of N\u2082/CH\u2084 mixtures provides a second HCN source. Surface aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde on montmorillonite yields 3-hydroxypropanal, which dehydrates to acrolein; Michael addition of NH\u2083 to acrolein produces 3-aminopropanal. HCN and H\u2082S are hub molecules: HCN participates in both cyanohydrin formation (step 1) and thione-to-nitrile exchange (step 4); H\u2082S is consumed in thiolation-cyclization (step 2) and regenerated in thione-to-nitrile exchange (step 4), creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. NH\u2083 is consumed in Michael addition and regenerated in cyclization and hydrolysis steps, establishing nitrogen economy. Note: the cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic proline; enantioselection to L-proline remains an open question, potentially involving chiral mineral surfaces or autocatalytic amplification.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c4-2-1-3-5/h2,5H,1,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-enal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acrolein\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O/c1-2-3-4/h2-3H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"proline\",\n      \"common_name\": \"proline (racemic)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"Cu\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"elemental copper\",\n      \"common_name\": \"native copper\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/Cu\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluids, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced by H\u2082 on the surface of greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), which serves as a structural and functional analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. The mineral surface activates H\u2082 and facilitates hydride transfer to the carbon of CO\u2082, producing formate (HCOO\u207b). This is the first step of carbon fixation analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate at hydrothermal conditions is experimentally demonstrated (Preiner et al., 2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution; Herschy et al., 2014). This provides the C1 building block for downstream organic synthesis. Formate is the primary product of abiotic CO\u2082 hydrogenation under alkaline vent conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Subseafloor hydrothermal conditions, moderate pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced by H\u2082 on magnetite/pyrite mineral surfaces to yield formaldehyde (HCHO). The mineral surface adsorbs formate and facilitates two-electron reduction with loss of the hydroxide/water. This is a thermodynamically challenging step driven by the high H\u2082 fugacity in serpentinization systems.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde production from formate reduction on iron oxide/sulfide minerals has been explored under hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska et al., 2017). While yields are low, the continuous production in flow-through hydrothermal systems and removal by downstream reactions shifts the equilibrium. Formaldehyde is a critical C1 feedstock for aldol chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions at black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces: CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO, which binds to the magnetite surface. Sequential hydrogenation and C\u2013C coupling on the mineral surface produces C2 oxygenates including acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). The magnetite surface provides the catalytic sites for CO dissociation, hydrogenation, and chain growth.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C1-C3 oxygenates on magnetite and other iron minerals under hydrothermal conditions has been experimentally demonstrated (McCollom et al., 1999, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres; Holm & Charlou, 2001). Acetaldehyde is among the products detected in FTT synthesis experiments with iron catalysts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent wall, pH gradient driven condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of formate with ammonia on mackinawite (FeS) mineral surfaces. The mineral surface activates formate toward nucleophilic attack by ammonia, forming formamide with loss of water. The alkaline vent pH gradient and elevated temperature drive the thermodynamically unfavorable condensation by coupling to the proton gradient across vent walls.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide formation from ammonium formate has been demonstrated at elevated temperatures (Saladino et al., 2012, Chemistry & Biodiversity). FeS minerals catalyze condensation reactions in hydrothermal settings (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). The vent pH gradient provides the thermodynamic driving force for this endergonic condensation (Lane & Martin, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decomposition of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Subaerial geothermal field, dry conditions, UV exposure; mineral-catalyzed dehydration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide undergoes dehydration to hydrogen cyanide on TiO\u2082 and clay mineral surfaces. The mineral surface adsorbs formamide and catalyzes the elimination of water, forming HCN. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis under UV irradiation can also drive this transformation. Montmorillonite provides additional surface area and acid-base catalysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO\u2082-catalyzed and UV-driven decomposition of formamide to HCN is well documented (Saladino et al., 2001, 2004, Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry). Mineral-catalyzed formamide decomposition is a major proposed route to HCN on early Earth surfaces. This connects hydrothermal formamide production to surface HCN availability for cyanosulfidic chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric UV photochemistry producing HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Upper atmosphere UV photolysis of N\u2082/CH\u2084 mixtures; HCN rains out to surface pools; TiO\u2082 particles in atmospheric dust may catalyze reactions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis of N\u2082 and CH\u2084 in the anoxic early Earth atmosphere produces radical intermediates (N atoms, CH\u2083 radicals, CH\u2082 radicals) that recombine to form HCN. The HCN is transported to the surface via rainout and dissolution in surface water bodies. This is analogous to the well-characterized HCN photochemistry observed in Titan's atmosphere.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Atmospheric HCN production from N\u2082/CH\u2084 photochemistry is extensively studied (Zahnle, 1986; Tian et al., 2011, Earth and Planetary Science Letters). This is considered a major prebiotic HCN source on early Earth, especially under reducing atmospheric conditions. The HCN yield depends on atmospheric CH\u2084/CO\u2082 ratio and UV flux. TiO\u2082 dust particles referenced as plausible atmospheric photocatalyst (Cleaves et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline evaporitic pool; clay mineral catalysis; Ca(OH)\u2082 or Mg(OH)\u2082 as base\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed aldol condensation: the \u03b1-hydrogen of acetaldehyde is abstracted to form an enolate, which attacks the carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde in a nucleophilic addition. This forms the \u03b2-hydroxy aldehyde 3-hydroxypropanal (hydracrylic aldehyde). Montmorillonite clay provides Br\u00f8nsted base sites and concentrates the reactants on its interlayer surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of simple aldehydes is a well-established prebiotic reaction (Breslow, 1959; Ricardo et al., 2004). Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol reactions has been documented (Joshi et al., 2009). This two-step approach (aldol then dehydration) to acrolein avoids the chemically questionable single-step formaldehyde trimerization criticized in the previous attempt. 3-Hydroxypropanal is the expected kinetic aldol product.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Dehydration of 3-hydroxypropanal to acrolein\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool; dehydration during dry phase; mild heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acid-catalyzed elimination (E1cb or E2 mechanism): the hydroxyl group at C3 of 3-hydroxypropanal is lost as water, with simultaneous formation of the C2=C3 double bond, yielding acrolein (prop-2-enal). This \u03b2-elimination is thermodynamically favorable and is promoted by clay mineral acid sites and heating during the dry phase of wet-dry cycles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dehydration of \u03b2-hydroxy aldehydes to \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehydes is a facile reaction under mildly acidic or thermal conditions (March, Advanced Organic Chemistry). Wet-dry cycling provides the thermal energy and reduced water activity needed for elimination. Montmorillonite clay provides Br\u00f8nsted acid catalysis. This step, combined with rxn_007, provides a chemically rigorous two-step route to acrolein from C1+C2 aldehydes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous evaporitic pool; slightly acidic to neutral pH for amine nucleophilicity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"1,4-conjugate addition (Michael addition): the lone pair of ammonia acts as a nucleophile, attacking the \u03b2-carbon (C3) of the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde acrolein. The resulting enolate tautomerizes to the aldehyde, yielding 3-aminopropanal. This is a straightforward 1,4-addition that preserves the aldehyde functionality needed for the subsequent Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Michael addition of amines to \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated carbonyls is well established in prebiotic chemistry. Patel et al. (2015) note that 3-aminopropanal can form from acrolein + NH\u2083 in the cyanosulfidic reaction network. Montmorillonite clay concentrates both ammonia and acrolein on its surface, promoting the bimolecular reaction. This provides the key C3 amino-aldehyde starting material for the proline ring synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation (Strecker-type)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic surface pool; ambient conditions; montmorillonite may concentrate reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal: HCN dissociates to CN\u207b, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of 3-aminopropanal, forming a new C\u2013C bond. Protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. The free primary amine at C4 is preserved for subsequent cyclization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation is Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). This C\u2013C bond-forming step extends the C3 amino-aldehyde to the C4 aminonitrile, establishing the chain length required for five-membered pyrrolidine ring formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions; H\u2082S atmosphere or dissolved H\u2082S; stibnite as sulfide mineral source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two sequential transformations in one pot: (1) Thiolation \u2014 H\u2082S attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a thioamide (C=S) functional group. (2) Intramolecular cyclization \u2014 the primary amine at C4 performs nucleophilic attack on the thioamide carbon, closing the five-membered pyrrolidine ring with expulsion of NH\u2083. The product is 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 2 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The simultaneous thiolation-cyclization is characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry, where H\u2082S activates nitriles toward ring closure. NH\u2083 released here is recycled into upstream Michael addition (rxn_009). Stibnite and other sulfide minerals serve as local H\u2082S sources in surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu\u2070)\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu\u2070)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic surface conditions; native copper deposits from Cu\u00b2\u207a reduction by H\u2082S\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive deoxygenation: the Cu\u2070/H\u2082S reducing system donates electrons to cleave the C3\u2013OH bond of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione. Elemental copper provides the reducing equivalents, with H\u2082S serving as a co-reductant and proton donor. The hydroxyl group is lost as water, yielding pyrrolidine-2-thione with a fully reduced pyrrolidine ring.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 3 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). Elemental copper is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper deposits form when dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions are reduced by H\u2082S in surface geochemical settings associated with sulfide mineralization. The Cu/H\u2082S system provides the exact reducing equivalents needed for C\u2013OH bond cleavage. Copper is represented as mol_019 in the network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Thione-to-nitrile exchange with HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions; HCN present in solution; montmorillonite concentrates reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide displaces the thione sulfur at C2 of pyrrolidine-2-thione: HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic thioamide carbon. The C=S bond is broken with release of H\u2082S, and a new C\u2013CN bond is formed, yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This converts a sulfur-containing functional group to a nitrogen-containing nitrile \u2014 a key interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry. The released H\u2082S is recycled back for use in rxn_011.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 4 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The thione-to-nitrile exchange demonstrates the elegant sulfur cycling central to cyanosulfidic chemistry: H\u2082S consumed in rxn_011 (thiolation-cyclization) is regenerated here, making sulfur catalytic. HCN is the second hub molecule consumed in this network (also used in rxn_010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous surface pool; 2 equivalents of H\u2082O consumed; metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) may catalyze hydrolysis; montmorillonite provides acid-base catalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential hydrolysis of the nitrile group (C\u2261N) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile: (1) water attacks the nitrile carbon nucleophilically, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide); (2) a second hydrolysis cleaves the amide to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed overall. The product is proline (racemic).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 5 (final) of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). Two H\u2082O are consumed (correcting the stoichiometry from the previous attempt). The released NH\u2083 is recycled into upstream reactions (rxn_009). Nitrile hydrolysis at ambient T and neutral pH can be slow (days-weeks); Fe\u00b2\u207a and Zn\u00b2\u207a ions or montmorillonite clay may catalyze the reaction. This rate-limiting step is an acknowledged open question in the literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Proline incorporation into oligopeptides via wet-dry cycling\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces; repeated dehydration-rehydration; proline introduces kinks and turns in peptide chains\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Peptide bond formation via condensation: the secondary amine of proline reacts with the carboxylic acid of another amino acid (or proline itself) during the dry phase, losing water to form a peptide bond. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the reaction by adsorbing and concentrating amino acids on its surface, and by providing Lewis acid catalysis. Repeated wet-dry cycles drive iterative peptide elongation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Clay-catalyzed peptide bond formation under wet-dry cycling is extensively demonstrated (Lahav et al., 1978; Bujd\u00e1k & Rode, 1999; Forsythe et al., 2015, Angewandte Chemie). Proline, as a cyclic imino acid with a rigid pyrrolidine ring, introduces conformational constraints (kinks, turns) into oligopeptides. This connects the surface-synthesized proline to biologically relevant macromolecule assembly. Note: this reaction is shown as self-referencing to indicate proline enters the peptide pool while remaining available.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Complete hydrothermal-to-surface cyanosulfidic pipeline\",\n      \"description\": \"The most complete pathway from CO\u2082 through hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface aldol chemistry for acrolein/3-aminopropanal synthesis, hydrothermal formamide-derived HCN, and the full 5-step Patel et al. cyanosulfidic core to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN + hydrothermal organics route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is sourced from atmospheric UV photochemistry of N\u2082/CH\u2084 (rxn_006), while C1-C2 aldehyde feedstocks come from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation. These converge at the surface for aldol \u2192 acrolein \u2192 3-aminopropanal \u2192 cyanosulfidic core \u2192 proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formamide-to-HCN pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is generated via a two-step hydrothermal-to-surface route: formate + NH\u2083 \u2192 formamide (hydrothermal, rxn_004), then formamide \u2192 HCN (surface thermal/UV, rxn_005). This HCN feeds into both the cyanohydrin step (rxn_010) and the thione-to-nitrile exchange (rxn_013) of the core cyanosulfidic pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Core cyanosulfidic proline synthesis (Patel et al. 2015)\",\n      \"description\": \"The experimentally demonstrated 5-step surface cyanosulfidic pathway from 3-aminopropanal + HCN through cyanohydrin formation, H\u2082S-mediated thiolation-cyclization, Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis to proline. This is the literature-established core.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch acetaldehyde to 3-aminopropanal route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis (rxn_003) is combined with hydrothermal-derived formaldehyde via surface aldol condensation (rxn_007) \u2192 dehydration to acrolein (rxn_008) \u2192 Michael addition of NH\u2083 (rxn_009) \u2192 cyanosulfidic core \u2192 proline. Emphasizes the hydrothermal C2 oxygenate supply.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Full pipeline from CO\u2082 to proline-containing peptides\",\n      \"description\": \"The complete prebiotic pipeline spanning all three environments: hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to C1-C2 building blocks, surface cyanosulfidic proline synthesis, and biochemical incorporation into oligopeptides via wet-dry cycling on clay. This pathway shows the full journey from inorganic carbon to biologically relevant macromolecules.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual HCN source convergence pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Demonstrates redundancy in HCN supply: atmospheric photochemistry (rxn_006) and hydrothermal formamide decomposition (rxn_004 \u2192 rxn_005) independently produce HCN, which converges at the surface pool where it is consumed by both cyanohydrin formation (rxn_010) and thione-to-nitrile exchange (rxn_013). This pathway highlights the network robustness from multiple HCN sources.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"H\u2082S sulfur cycling route (hydrothermal supply \u2192 catalytic turnover)\",\n      \"description\": \"Traces the complete lifecycle of H\u2082S: produced in hydrothermal vents, transported to surface pools where it is consumed in thiolation-cyclization (rxn_011) and reductive deoxygenation (rxn_012), then regenerated in thione-to-nitrile exchange (rxn_013). The regenerated H\u2082S feeds back into rxn_011, creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. Complete route from hydrothermal H\u2082S through all core steps to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"NH\u2083 nitrogen economy route (consumption and regeneration)\",\n      \"description\": \"Traces the nitrogen economy: NH\u2083 is consumed in Michael addition to acrolein (rxn_009, producing 3-aminopropanal) and regenerated in both thiolation-cyclization (rxn_011, 1 equiv NH\u2083) and nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_014, 1 equiv NH\u2083). The regenerated NH\u2083 re-enters the cycle at rxn_009. Complete route from atmospherically-sourced HCN through all steps to proline, emphasizing autocatalytic nitrogen cycling.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-to-formaldehyde aldol route to 3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"description\": \"Focuses on the formaldehyde supply chain: hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation produces formate (rxn_001), which is reduced to formaldehyde (rxn_002). Formaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with acetaldehyde (rxn_007) \u2192 3-hydroxypropanal \u2192 acrolein (rxn_008) \u2192 3-aminopropanal (rxn_009). This route through the C1\u2192C3 chain elongation feeds into the cyanosulfidic core to produce proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN \u2014 produced by two independent routes (atmospheric photochemistry rxn_006 and formamide decomposition rxn_005), consumed by two distinct reactions (cyanohydrin formation rxn_010 and thione-to-nitrile exchange rxn_013)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"NH\u2083 \u2014 consumed in Michael addition to acrolein (rxn_009) and formate condensation (rxn_004); regenerated in thiolation-cyclization (rxn_011) and nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_014). Creates an autocatalytic nitrogen cycle.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"H\u2082S \u2014 consumed in thiolation-cyclization (rxn_011) and reductive deoxygenation (rxn_012); regenerated in thione-to-nitrile exchange (rxn_013). Creates a catalytic sulfur cycle within the cyanosulfidic framework.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"3-aminopropanal \u2014 the key C3 amino-aldehyde hub produced by Michael addition of NH\u2083 to acrolein (rxn_009), consumed by cyanohydrin formation (rxn_010) as entry point to the cyanosulfidic core. All upstream pathways converge here.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyrrolidine-2-thione \u2014 central cyclic intermediate produced by reductive deoxygenation (rxn_012), consumed by thione-to-nitrile exchange (rxn_013). Junction between ring-forming and nitrile/hydrolysis steps.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Proline (racemic, prebiotically produced)", "overall_strategy": "The network implements the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline synthesis from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) as the core 5-step pathway, embedded within a broader prebiotic feedstock-generation network spanning hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. The core pathway converts 3-aminopropanal through cyanohydrin formation, H\u2082S-mediated thiolation-cyclization, Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis to yield proline. Upstream, hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on greigite/magnetite produces formate, formaldehyde, and acetaldehyde; formate condenses with NH\u2083 on mackinawite to yield formamide, which decomposes to HCN. Independently, atmospheric UV photochemistry of N\u2082/CH\u2084 mixtures provides a second HCN source. Surface aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde on montmorillonite yields 3-hydroxypropanal, which dehydrates to acrolein; Michael addition of NH\u2083 to acrolein produces 3-aminopropanal. HCN and H\u2082S are hub molecules: HCN participates in both cyanohydrin formation (step 1) and thione-to-nitrile exchange (step 4); H\u2082S is consumed in thiolation-cyclization (step 2) and regenerated in thione-to-nitrile exchange (step 4), creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. NH\u2083 is consumed in Michael addition and regenerated in cyclization and hydrolysis steps, establishing nitrogen economy. Note: the cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic proline; enantioselection to L-proline remains an open question, potentially involving chiral mineral surfaces or autocatalytic amplification.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "3-hydroxypropanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c4-2-1-3-5/h2,5H,1,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O", "iupac_name": "prop-2-enal", "common_name": "acrolein", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O/c1-2-3-4/h2-3H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H7NO", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanal", "common_name": "3-aminopropanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H7NOS", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "common_name": "3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H7NS", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-thione", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-thione", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "proline", "common_name": "proline (racemic)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "Cu", "iupac_name": "elemental copper", "common_name": "native copper", "inchi": "InChI=1S/Cu", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluids, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is reduced by H\u2082 on the surface of greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), which serves as a structural and functional analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. The mineral surface activates H\u2082 and facilitates hydride transfer to the carbon of CO\u2082, producing formate (HCOO\u207b). This is the first step of carbon fixation analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate at hydrothermal conditions is experimentally demonstrated (Preiner et al., 2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution; Herschy et al., 2014). This provides the C1 building block for downstream organic synthesis. Formate is the primary product of abiotic CO\u2082 hydrogenation under alkaline vent conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Subseafloor hydrothermal conditions, moderate pH"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced by H\u2082 on magnetite/pyrite mineral surfaces to yield formaldehyde (HCHO). The mineral surface adsorbs formate and facilitates two-electron reduction with loss of the hydroxide/water. This is a thermodynamically challenging step driven by the high H\u2082 fugacity in serpentinization systems.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde production from formate reduction on iron oxide/sulfide minerals has been explored under hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska et al., 2017). While yields are low, the continuous production in flow-through hydrothermal systems and removal by downstream reactions shifts the equilibrium. Formaldehyde is a critical C1 feedstock for aldol chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions at black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal systems"}, "mechanism": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces: CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO, which binds to the magnetite surface. Sequential hydrogenation and C\u2013C coupling on the mineral surface produces C2 oxygenates including acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). The magnetite surface provides the catalytic sites for CO dissociation, hydrogenation, and chain growth.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C1-C3 oxygenates on magnetite and other iron minerals under hydrothermal conditions has been experimentally demonstrated (McCollom et al., 1999, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres; Holm & Charlou, 2001). Acetaldehyde is among the products detected in FTT synthesis experiments with iron catalysts."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent wall, pH gradient driven condensation"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of formate with ammonia on mackinawite (FeS) mineral surfaces. The mineral surface activates formate toward nucleophilic attack by ammonia, forming formamide with loss of water. The alkaline vent pH gradient and elevated temperature drive the thermodynamically unfavorable condensation by coupling to the proton gradient across vent walls.", "reasoning": "Formamide formation from ammonium formate has been demonstrated at elevated temperatures (Saladino et al., 2012, Chemistry & Biodiversity). FeS minerals catalyze condensation reactions in hydrothermal settings (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). The vent pH gradient provides the thermodynamic driving force for this endergonic condensation (Lane & Martin, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Thermal decomposition of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Subaerial geothermal field, dry conditions, UV exposure; mineral-catalyzed dehydration"}, "mechanism": "Formamide undergoes dehydration to hydrogen cyanide on TiO\u2082 and clay mineral surfaces. The mineral surface adsorbs formamide and catalyzes the elimination of water, forming HCN. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis under UV irradiation can also drive this transformation. Montmorillonite provides additional surface area and acid-base catalysis.", "reasoning": "TiO\u2082-catalyzed and UV-driven decomposition of formamide to HCN is well documented (Saladino et al., 2001, 2004, Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry). Mineral-catalyzed formamide decomposition is a major proposed route to HCN on early Earth surfaces. This connects hydrothermal formamide production to surface HCN availability for cyanosulfidic chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Atmospheric UV photochemistry producing HCN", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "Upper atmosphere UV photolysis of N\u2082/CH\u2084 mixtures; HCN rains out to surface pools; TiO\u2082 particles in atmospheric dust may catalyze reactions"}, "mechanism": "UV photolysis of N\u2082 and CH\u2084 in the anoxic early Earth atmosphere produces radical intermediates (N atoms, CH\u2083 radicals, CH\u2082 radicals) that recombine to form HCN. The HCN is transported to the surface via rainout and dissolution in surface water bodies. This is analogous to the well-characterized HCN photochemistry observed in Titan's atmosphere.", "reasoning": "Atmospheric HCN production from N\u2082/CH\u2084 photochemistry is extensively studied (Zahnle, 1986; Tian et al., 2011, Earth and Planetary Science Letters). This is considered a major prebiotic HCN source on early Earth, especially under reducing atmospheric conditions. The HCN yield depends on atmospheric CH\u2084/CO\u2082 ratio and UV flux. TiO\u2082 dust particles referenced as plausible atmospheric photocatalyst (Cleaves et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline evaporitic pool; clay mineral catalysis; Ca(OH)\u2082 or Mg(OH)\u2082 as base"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed aldol condensation: the \u03b1-hydrogen of acetaldehyde is abstracted to form an enolate, which attacks the carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde in a nucleophilic addition. This forms the \u03b2-hydroxy aldehyde 3-hydroxypropanal (hydracrylic aldehyde). Montmorillonite clay provides Br\u00f8nsted base sites and concentrates the reactants on its interlayer surfaces.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of simple aldehydes is a well-established prebiotic reaction (Breslow, 1959; Ricardo et al., 2004). Montmorillonite catalysis of aldol reactions has been documented (Joshi et al., 2009). This two-step approach (aldol then dehydration) to acrolein avoids the chemically questionable single-step formaldehyde trimerization criticized in the previous attempt. 3-Hydroxypropanal is the expected kinetic aldol product."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Dehydration of 3-hydroxypropanal to acrolein", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool; dehydration during dry phase; mild heating"}, "mechanism": "Acid-catalyzed elimination (E1cb or E2 mechanism): the hydroxyl group at C3 of 3-hydroxypropanal is lost as water, with simultaneous formation of the C2=C3 double bond, yielding acrolein (prop-2-enal). This \u03b2-elimination is thermodynamically favorable and is promoted by clay mineral acid sites and heating during the dry phase of wet-dry cycles.", "reasoning": "Dehydration of \u03b2-hydroxy aldehydes to \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehydes is a facile reaction under mildly acidic or thermal conditions (March, Advanced Organic Chemistry). Wet-dry cycling provides the thermal energy and reduced water activity needed for elimination. Montmorillonite clay provides Br\u00f8nsted acid catalysis. This step, combined with rxn_007, provides a chemically rigorous two-step route to acrolein from C1+C2 aldehydes."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous evaporitic pool; slightly acidic to neutral pH for amine nucleophilicity"}, "mechanism": "1,4-conjugate addition (Michael addition): the lone pair of ammonia acts as a nucleophile, attacking the \u03b2-carbon (C3) of the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde acrolein. The resulting enolate tautomerizes to the aldehyde, yielding 3-aminopropanal. This is a straightforward 1,4-addition that preserves the aldehyde functionality needed for the subsequent Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation.", "reasoning": "Michael addition of amines to \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated carbonyls is well established in prebiotic chemistry. Patel et al. (2015) note that 3-aminopropanal can form from acrolein + NH\u2083 in the cyanosulfidic reaction network. Montmorillonite clay concentrates both ammonia and acrolein on its surface, promoting the bimolecular reaction. This provides the key C3 amino-aldehyde starting material for the proline ring synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation (Strecker-type)", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic surface pool; ambient conditions; montmorillonite may concentrate reactants"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal: HCN dissociates to CN\u207b, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of 3-aminopropanal, forming a new C\u2013C bond. Protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. The free primary amine at C4 is preserved for subsequent cyclization.", "reasoning": "Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation is Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). This C\u2013C bond-forming step extends the C3 amino-aldehyde to the C4 aminonitrile, establishing the chain length required for five-membered pyrrolidine ring formation."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions; H\u2082S atmosphere or dissolved H\u2082S; stibnite as sulfide mineral source"}, "mechanism": "Two sequential transformations in one pot: (1) Thiolation \u2014 H\u2082S attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a thioamide (C=S) functional group. (2) Intramolecular cyclization \u2014 the primary amine at C4 performs nucleophilic attack on the thioamide carbon, closing the five-membered pyrrolidine ring with expulsion of NH\u2083. The product is 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione.", "reasoning": "This is Step 2 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The simultaneous thiolation-cyclization is characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry, where H\u2082S activates nitriles toward ring closure. NH\u2083 released here is recycled into upstream Michael addition (rxn_009). Stibnite and other sulfide minerals serve as local H\u2082S sources in surface settings."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_019", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu\u2070)", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu\u2070)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic surface conditions; native copper deposits from Cu\u00b2\u207a reduction by H\u2082S"}, "mechanism": "Reductive deoxygenation: the Cu\u2070/H\u2082S reducing system donates electrons to cleave the C3\u2013OH bond of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione. Elemental copper provides the reducing equivalents, with H\u2082S serving as a co-reductant and proton donor. The hydroxyl group is lost as water, yielding pyrrolidine-2-thione with a fully reduced pyrrolidine ring.", "reasoning": "This is Step 3 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). Elemental copper is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper deposits form when dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions are reduced by H\u2082S in surface geochemical settings associated with sulfide mineralization. The Cu/H\u2082S system provides the exact reducing equivalents needed for C\u2013OH bond cleavage. Copper is represented as mol_019 in the network."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Thione-to-nitrile exchange with HCN", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions; HCN present in solution; montmorillonite concentrates reactants"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide displaces the thione sulfur at C2 of pyrrolidine-2-thione: HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic thioamide carbon. The C=S bond is broken with release of H\u2082S, and a new C\u2013CN bond is formed, yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This converts a sulfur-containing functional group to a nitrogen-containing nitrile \u2014 a key interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry. The released H\u2082S is recycled back for use in rxn_011.", "reasoning": "This is Step 4 of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The thione-to-nitrile exchange demonstrates the elegant sulfur cycling central to cyanosulfidic chemistry: H\u2082S consumed in rxn_011 (thiolation-cyclization) is regenerated here, making sulfur catalytic. HCN is the second hub molecule consumed in this network (also used in rxn_010)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis to proline", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous surface pool; 2 equivalents of H\u2082O consumed; metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) may catalyze hydrolysis; montmorillonite provides acid-base catalysis"}, "mechanism": "Sequential hydrolysis of the nitrile group (C\u2261N) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile: (1) water attacks the nitrile carbon nucleophilically, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide); (2) a second hydrolysis cleaves the amide to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed overall. The product is proline (racemic).", "reasoning": "This is Step 5 (final) of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway from Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). Two H\u2082O are consumed (correcting the stoichiometry from the previous attempt). The released NH\u2083 is recycled into upstream reactions (rxn_009). Nitrile hydrolysis at ambient T and neutral pH can be slow (days-weeks); Fe\u00b2\u207a and Zn\u00b2\u207a ions or montmorillonite clay may catalyze the reaction. This rate-limiting step is an acknowledged open question in the literature."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Proline incorporation into oligopeptides via wet-dry cycling", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces; repeated dehydration-rehydration; proline introduces kinks and turns in peptide chains"}, "mechanism": "Peptide bond formation via condensation: the secondary amine of proline reacts with the carboxylic acid of another amino acid (or proline itself) during the dry phase, losing water to form a peptide bond. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the reaction by adsorbing and concentrating amino acids on its surface, and by providing Lewis acid catalysis. Repeated wet-dry cycles drive iterative peptide elongation.", "reasoning": "Clay-catalyzed peptide bond formation under wet-dry cycling is extensively demonstrated (Lahav et al., 1978; Bujd\u00e1k & Rode, 1999; Forsythe et al., 2015, Angewandte Chemie). Proline, as a cyclic imino acid with a rigid pyrrolidine ring, introduces conformational constraints (kinks, turns) into oligopeptides. This connects the surface-synthesized proline to biologically relevant macromolecule assembly. Note: this reaction is shown as self-referencing to indicate proline enters the peptide pool while remaining available."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Complete hydrothermal-to-surface cyanosulfidic pipeline", "description": "The most complete pathway from CO\u2082 through hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface aldol chemistry for acrolein/3-aminopropanal synthesis, hydrothermal formamide-derived HCN, and the full 5-step Patel et al. cyanosulfidic core to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "r