{"timestamp": "2026-03-18T10:09:03.137450", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Proline: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nOne experimentally demonstrated pathway produces L-Proline (C5H9NO2, SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C(=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8), MW: 115.13) from prebiotically available precursors via cyanosulfidic chemistry in surface environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Pyrrolidine Route (Surface Environment)\n\nThis 5-step pathway builds the pyrrolidine ring of proline through a sequence of cyanohydrin formation, thiolation-cyclization, reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis. The entire chemistry was demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) as part of the cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework.\n\n**Step 1 \u2014 Cyanohydrin formation**: 3-aminopropanal + HCN \u2192 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\n- SMILES: NCCC=O.C#N>>N#CC(O)CCN\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation \u2014 hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03) undergoes nucleophilic addition to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal (C3H7NO, SMILES: C(CN)C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2, MW: 73.09). The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, forming a new C\u2013C bond and yielding the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: C(CN)C(C#N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2, MW: 100.12). The free amine group on the 3-aminopropanal is preserved for subsequent cyclization.\n\n**Step 2 \u2014 Thiolation and cyclization**: 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile + H\u2082S \u2192 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCN.S>>OC1CCNC1=S.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, H\u2082S atmosphere\n- Mechanism: Hydrogen sulfide (H2S, SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2, MW: 34.08) attacks the nitrile carbon of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, converting the C\u2261N group to a thioamide (C=S). The primary amine at the opposite end of the chain then undergoes intramolecular cyclization by attacking the thioamide carbon, forming the five-membered pyrrolidine ring. This produces 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione (C4H7NOS, SMILES: C1CNC(=S)C1O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7), MW: 117.17) with release of ammonia (NH3, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03). This step simultaneously achieves ring closure and introduces the thione functional group that is central to the subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations.\n\n**Step 3 \u2014 Reductive deoxygenation**: 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-thione + H\u2082O\n- SMILES: OC1CCNC1=S>>S=C1CCCN1.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H\u2082S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu], SMILES: [Cu])\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Mechanism: Reductive deoxygenation \u2014 the hydroxyl group at C3 of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione is removed with loss of water (H2O, SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2, MW: 18.01). Elemental copper acts as a reductant in concert with hydrogen sulfide. The Cu/H\u2082S system provides the reducing equivalents needed to cleave the C\u2013OH bond, yielding pyrrolidine-2-thione (C4H7NS, SMILES: C1CC(=S)NC1, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6), MW: 101.17). This step is critical for producing the fully reduced pyrrolidine ring needed for the final proline product.\n\n**Step 4 \u2014 Thione-to-nitrile exchange**: pyrrolidine-2-thione + HCN \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + H\u2082S\n- SMILES: S=C1CCCN1.C#N>>N#CC1CCCN1.S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, HCN present\n- Mechanism: The thione (C=S) group of pyrrolidine-2-thione is displaced by cyanide. HCN attacks the thioamide carbon, replacing the sulfur with a nitrile group. This thione-to-nitrile exchange releases H\u2082S and produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (C5H8N2, SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2, MW: 96.13). The released H\u2082S is recycled back into the cyanosulfidic network. This reaction converts the sulfur-containing heterocycle into a nitrile-bearing pyrrolidine that can undergo hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (proline).\n\n**Step 5 \u2014 Nitrile hydrolysis**: pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 L-Proline + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC1CCCN1.O.O>>N.O=C(O)C1CCCN1\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Mechanism: Hydrolysis of the nitrile group (C\u2261N) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon nucleophilically, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide), which undergoes a second hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed. The product is L-Proline (C5H9NO2, SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C(=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8), MW: 115.13), a cyclic (pyrrolidine-containing) amino acid.\n\nThis 5-step pathway is notable because it constructs the pyrrolidine ring \u2014 a structural feature unique to proline among the proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 through cyanosulfidic chemistry. The pathway showcases the role of H\u2082S and HCN as interconverting sulfur and nitrogen functional groups through thioamide and nitrile intermediates, a hallmark of the Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: C(CN)C(C#N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Key branch-point intermediate** \u2014 this aminonitrile cyanohydrin is the product of the Strecker-type addition of HCN to 3-aminopropanal. It contains both the free amine and nitrile groups required for the subsequent thiolation-cyclization step that forms the pyrrolidine ring. It is consumed by H\u2082S-mediated cyclization to produce 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n### Hub Molecule: pyrrolidine-2-thione (C4H7NS)\n- Formula: C4H7NS\n- SMILES: C1CC(=S)NC1\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 101.17\n- Role: **Central cyclic intermediate** \u2014 pyrrolidine-2-thione is the reduced pyrrolidine ring bearing a thione group. It is produced by reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione (using Cu/H\u2082S), and consumed by thione-to-nitrile exchange with HCN to produce pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This molecule sits at the junction between the ring-formation steps and the nitrile/hydrolysis steps that produce proline (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n### Hub Molecule: hydrogen cyanide (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: **Upstream hub \u2014 carbon and nitrogen source** \u2014 HCN participates in two distinct reactions in the network: (1) Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation with 3-aminopropanal (Step 1), and (2) thione-to-nitrile exchange with pyrrolidine-2-thione (Step 4). HCN is a prebiotically abundant molecule produced by atmospheric photochemistry (UV irradiation of N\u2082/CH\u2084/CO\u2082 mixtures), volcanic outgassing, and impact-generated synthesis.\n\n### Hub Molecule: hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S)\n- Formula: H2S\n- SMILES: S\n- InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\n- MW: 34.08\n- Role: **Recycled sulfur carrier** \u2014 H\u2082S is consumed in Step 2 (thiolation-cyclization) and regenerated in Step 4 (thione-to-nitrile exchange), creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. It also serves as a co-reductant with elemental copper in Step 3 (reductive deoxygenation). H\u2082S is prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing and hydrothermal vents.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**3-aminopropanal** (C3H7NO)\n- Formula: C3H7NO\n- SMILES: C(CN)C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\n- MW: 73.09\n- Role: Starting material \u2014 the C3 amino aldehyde that provides the carbon backbone and amine nitrogen for the pyrrolidine ring. 3-aminopropanal can form prebiotically from acrolein (propenal) + NH\u2083, or from Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein. It is produced in cyanosulfidic reaction networks from simple C1\u2013C3 feedstocks (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n**3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione** (C4H7NOS)\n- Formula: C4H7NOS\n- SMILES: C1CNC(=S)C1O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)\n- MW: 117.17\n- Role: First cyclic intermediate \u2014 formed by H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. Retains a hydroxyl group at C3 that is removed in the subsequent reductive deoxygenation step. This intermediate demonstrates the simultaneous ring closure and thione formation that is characteristic of cyanosulfidic pyrrolidine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n**pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile** (C5H8N2)\n- Formula: C5H8N2\n- SMILES: C1CC(NC1)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\n- MW: 96.13\n- Role: Penultimate intermediate \u2014 the nitrile-bearing pyrrolidine produced by thione-to-nitrile exchange. Both the pyrrolidine ring and the C5 carbon skeleton are complete at this stage; only hydrolysis of the nitrile to a carboxylic acid remains to yield proline (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n**Ammonia** (NH\u2083)\n- Formula: H3N\n- SMILES: N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- MW: 17.03\n- Role: Byproduct released in Step 2 (cyclization) and Step 5 (nitrile hydrolysis). Prebiotically abundant from volcanic outgassing, atmospheric photochemistry, and hydrothermal systems. Recycled as nitrogen source for other prebiotic reactions.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H\u2082O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H\u2082S** (hydrogen sulfide): SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\n- **NH\u2083** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **3-aminopropanal**: SMILES: C(CN)C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reaction R1: Cyanohydrin formation (Strecker-type)\n- 3-aminopropanal + HCN \u2192 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\n- SMILES: NCCC=O.C#N>>N#CC(O)CCN\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal, forming the cyanohydrin (\u03b1-hydroxynitrile) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. This is the carbon\u2013carbon bond forming step that extends the C3 aldehyde to the C4 aminonitrile, setting up the chain length needed for pyrrolidine ring formation.\n\n### Reaction R2: Thiolation-cyclization\n- 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile + H\u2082S \u2192 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC(O)CCN.S>>OC1CCNC1=S.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, H\u2082S atmosphere\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: H\u2082S attacks the nitrile carbon, converting C\u2261N to a thioamide (C=S). The terminal amine then performs intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the thioamide carbon, closing the five-membered pyrrolidine ring and releasing NH\u2083. This one-pot thiolation-cyclization is characteristic of cyanosulfidic chemistry, where H\u2082S activates nitriles toward cyclization.\n\n### Reaction R3: Reductive deoxygenation\n- 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-thione + H\u2082O\n- SMILES: OC1CCNC1=S>>S=C1CCCN1.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H\u2082S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu], SMILES: [Cu])\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Reductive removal of the C3 hydroxyl group. The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system donates electrons to cleave the C\u2013OH bond, producing the fully reduced pyrrolidine-2-thione with loss of water. Elemental copper is a plausible prebiotic reductant in cyanosulfidic scenarios \u2014 copper deposits are formed by reduction of dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a by H\u2082S in surface geochemical settings.\n\n### Reaction R4: Thione-to-nitrile exchange\n- pyrrolidine-2-thione + HCN \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + H\u2082S\n- SMILES: S=C1CCCN1.C#N>>N#CC1CCCN1.S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature, HCN present\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Cyanide displaces the thione sulfur at C2 of the pyrrolidine ring. HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic thioamide carbon. The C=S bond is broken with release of H\u2082S, and a new C\u2013CN bond is formed, yielding the nitrile. This reaction converts a sulfur-containing functional group to a nitrogen-containing one \u2014 a key interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry. The released H\u2082S is recycled for use in Step 2 (thiolation-cyclization).\n\n### Reaction R5: Nitrile hydrolysis\n- pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 L-Proline + NH\u2083\n- SMILES: N#CC1CCCN1.O.O>>N.O=C(O)C1CCCN1\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Sequential hydrolysis of the nitrile group \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide), which undergoes further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed. This completes the conversion of the nitrile to the carboxylate, yielding L-Proline.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe following agents are experimentally documented for reactions in the L-Proline synthesis network:\n\n- **Elemental copper (Cu\u2070)**: Metallic copper (SMILES: [Cu]). Acts as a reductant in the Cu/H\u2082S system for the reductive deoxygenation of 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione to pyrrolidine-2-thione (Reaction R3). Elemental copper is prebiotically plausible \u2014 native copper deposits form when dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions are reduced by H\u2082S in geochemical settings. Copper is found in hydrothermal and surface environments associated with sulfide mineralization. Used in: reductive deoxygenation (Patel et al., 2015).\n\n- **Hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S)**: Sulfidic acid (SMILES: S). Dual role: (1) acts as a co-reductant with elemental copper in the reductive deoxygenation step (Reaction R3), and (2) serves as the sulfur source for thiolation-cyclization (Reaction R2) and is regenerated by thione-to-nitrile exchange (Reaction R4). H\u2082S is abundantly available from volcanic outgassing, hydrothermal vents, and sulfide mineral dissolution. Used in: thiolation-cyclization (Reaction R2) and reductive deoxygenation (Reaction R3).\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN, H\u2082S, and simple aldehydes that produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids under plausible prebiotic surface conditions. For proline specifically, this study established the complete 5-step pathway from 3-aminopropanal + HCN through a series of cyanosulfidic transformations: (1) cyanohydrin formation \u2192 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, (2) H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization \u2192 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione, (3) Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-thione, (4) HCN-driven thione-to-nitrile exchange \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and (5) nitrile hydrolysis \u2192 L-Proline. The pathway is notable for constructing the pyrrolidine ring \u2014 unique among proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 through cyanosulfidic ring closure rather than through conventional Strecker synthesis, which cannot form cyclic amino acids. The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system used in Step 3 demonstrates that prebiotically available metals and sulfur species can drive reductive transformations needed for amino acid synthesis. The recycling of H\u2082S (consumed in Step 2, regenerated in Step 4) exemplifies the catalytic sulfur cycling central to the cyanosulfidic framework.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary)\nAll five reactions in the L-Proline synthesis pathway operate under surface cyanosulfidic conditions:\n- **Evaporitic pools and geothermal surface settings**: The reactions occur at ambient temperature and pressure in aqueous solution, consistent with shallow surface pools near volcanic/geothermal sources where HCN and H\u2082S are delivered by outgassing.\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions**: The pathway requires co-availability of HCN and H\u2082S \u2014 conditions found at the interface of volcanic degassing zones and surface water bodies. UV irradiation (relevant for other cyanosulfidic transformations) may also play a role in generating or activating some of the feedstocks.\n- **Copper availability**: Elemental copper for the reductive deoxygenation step (Reaction R3) is prebiotically plausible in surface settings where dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions from weathered copper minerals are reduced by H\u2082S to deposit native copper.\n- **3-Aminopropanal production**: The starting material 3-aminopropanal is itself a product of cyanosulfidic/surface chemistry \u2014 it can form from acrolein (produced by formaldehyde condensation or thermal decomposition of glycerol) reacting with ammonia, or from reductive amination of malondialdehyde.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\n- **Surface \u2192 Biochemical**: L-Proline produced by this pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool. As a cyclic imino acid with a rigid pyrrolidine ring, proline introduces structural constraints (kinks and turns) into prebiotic peptides. Proline-containing peptides formed by wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces in the Biochemical environment would have distinct conformational properties compared to peptides composed only of linear amino acids.\n- **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Simple feedstock molecules (HCN, H\u2082S, NH\u2083, aldehydes) can be produced in hydrothermal environments and transported to surface pools via ocean circulation and volcanic outgassing, where they fuel the cyanosulfidic proline synthesis pathway.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **3-Aminopropanal availability**: The pathway begins with 3-aminopropanal, a reactive amino aldehyde whose prebiotic concentration and stability in surface pools is uncertain. As an aldehyde, it is susceptible to oxidation, polymerization, and reaction with other nucleophiles present in the prebiotic milieu. The flux of 3-aminopropanal production versus its consumption by competing reactions is a key constraint on this pathway.\n\n2. **Chirality**: The cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic proline (equal L and D). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-proline) is unresolved. Possible enantioselection mechanisms include asymmetric crystallization, chiral mineral surfaces, or amplification through autocatalytic cycles, but none has been definitively demonstrated for proline.\n\n3. **Copper availability and oxidation state**: The reductive deoxygenation step (Reaction R3) requires elemental copper (Cu\u2070). While native copper can form from Cu\u00b2\u207a reduction by H\u2082S, the steady-state concentration of Cu\u2070 in prebiotic surface environments is poorly constrained. Whether sufficient Cu\u2070 would persist in the presence of other oxidants and complexing agents is an open question.\n\n4. **Cyclic vs. linear amino acid selectivity**: The cyanosulfidic pathway is specific to cyclic amino acids (proline) because the cyclization step (Reaction R2) depends on the intramolecular distance between the amine and the thioamide. For 3-aminopropanal, this distance is exactly right for five-membered ring formation. Whether similar pathways could produce other ring sizes (e.g., pipecolic acid from 4-aminobutanal) is an interesting extension.\n\n5. **H\u2082S recycling efficiency**: The pathway features an elegant sulfur cycle where H\u2082S is consumed in Step 2 and regenerated in Step 4. However, the efficiency of this recycling under real prebiotic conditions \u2014 with H\u2082S loss to oxidation, mineral precipitation (as metal sulfides), and atmospheric escape \u2014 may limit the catalytic turnover.\n\n6. **Nitrile hydrolysis rate**: The final step (Reaction R5) requires hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to the carboxylic acid. Nitrile hydrolysis at ambient temperature and neutral pH can be slow (days to weeks). The kinetics of this step under realistic prebiotic conditions (variable pH, temperature fluctuations, presence of metal ions that could catalyze hydrolysis) need further characterization.\n\n7. **Yield and selectivity**: While Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated all the individual steps, the overall yield of proline through the complete 5-step sequence has not been reported for a one-pot continuous process. Side reactions at each step (particularly the competing intermolecular reactions of the aminonitrile intermediate) could reduce the net yield significantly.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-constructed synthesis network that faithfully implements the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic proline synthesis as its core (rxn_009\u2013rxn_013), and extends it with plausible upstream feedstock generation in hydrothermal (CO\u2082 fixation to formate/formaldehyde/formamide) and surface (atmospheric HCN photochemistry) environments. The network topology is strong: 18 molecules and 13 reactions with 5 well-connected hub molecules (HCN degree 4, NH\u2083 degree 5, H\u2082S degree 3, formate degree 3, formamide degree 3). Convergent pathways to HCN from two independent sources (atmospheric photochemistry and formamide decomposition) provide network robustness. The H\u2082S and NH\u2083 recycling loops correctly capture the autocatalytic features of cyanosulfidic chemistry. Literature alignment is excellent \u2014 all 5 core cyanosulfidic steps match Patel et al. 2015 precisely, with correct intermediates (4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-thione, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile). Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_007 (formaldehyde \u2192 acrolein) is oversimplified and chemically questionable as a single step \u2014 this is the weakest link in the network; (2) elemental copper for rxn_011 is not represented as a molecule node; (3) rxn_013 stoichiometry should consume 2 H\u2082O; (4) the network claims to produce L-Proline but the cyanosulfidic pathway produces a racemic mixture \u2014 chirality is not addressed; (5) rxn_004 lacks mineral specification for a surface reaction. Despite these issues, the network demonstrates strong chemical reasoning, excellent literature alignment, and meaningful environmental interconnection.\n- Issues: ['Uses atmospheric UV photochemistry of N\u2082/CH\u2084 (well-established Titan-like chemistry) to supply HCN for the cyanohydrin step. Still depends on the problematic rxn_007 for acrolein/3-aminopropanal. This pathway only has 6 steps described but needs formaldehyde from somewhere \u2014 missing the explicit upstream source for 3-aminopropanal in this pathway description.', 'Routes through surface formate\u2013ammonia condensation. rxn_004 should specify a mineral catalyst for the surface condensation. The formate + NH\u2083 \u2192 formamide step is thermodynamically unfavorable without activation energy input or catalysis. Still contains the problematic rxn_007.', 'This is a partial pathway (3 steps) providing atmospheric HCN for the thione-to-nitrile exchange. It does not independently produce proline \u2014 it is a branch that feeds into the main pathway. As a standalone pathway it is incomplete.', \"Correctly identifies the H\u2082S catalytic sulfur cycle (consumed in rxn_010, regenerated in rxn_012) as described in Patel et al. 2015. This is an important feature of the cyanosulfidic framework. However, as a 'pathway' it is really a sub-cycle within the main pathway, not a route to the target.\", 'Correctly identifies ammonia recycling: NH\u2083 is consumed in rxn_008 (Michael addition) and regenerated in rxn_010 (cyclization) and rxn_013 (hydrolysis). This autocatalytic feedback is a genuine feature of the cyanosulfidic network. The pathway as described shows the nitrogen economy well.', 'A branch pathway supplying HCN from hydrothermal formamide for the thione-to-nitrile exchange step. Chemically sound but incomplete as a route to proline \u2014 only covers HCN supply and the last two transformations.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.88\n- Feedback: This is an excellent prebiotic synthesis network for racemic proline. The core strength is the faithful implementation of the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway (P4), which is experimentally validated and correctly represented with all five steps, proper intermediates, and the Cu/H\u2082S reducing system. The network embeds this core within a broader feedstock-generation framework spanning hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation, atmospheric photochemistry, and surface organic chemistry, creating a well-connected multi-environment network.\n\nStrengths: (1) Direct alignment with published experimental work (Patel et al. 2015, Nature Chemistry). (2) Dual HCN sources (formamide decomposition + atmospheric photochemistry) providing convergent feedstock generation. (3) Proper representation of H\u2082S and NH\u2083 catalytic cycling. (4) Mineral agents specified for hydrothermal and surface steps (greigite, magnetite, mackinawite, montmorillonite, native copper). (5) Honest acknowledgment that the pathway produces racemic proline with chirality as an open question.\n\nWeaknesses: (1) rxn_002 (formate\u2192formaldehyde) is less experimentally constrained. (2) rxn_003 (FTT acetaldehyde) lacks specific mineral catalyst citation. (3) rxn_015 is a degenerate self-loop that doesn't properly represent peptide formation. (4) mol_013 (3-aminopropanal) and mol_016 (pyrrolidine-2-thione) are labeled as hub molecules but only have degree 2 in the network graph. (5) The network could benefit from explicit H\u2082S source specification (e.g., hydrothermal vent outgassing).\n\nOverall, the network is well-designed, chemically sound, and strongly literature-supported. The topology has good connectivity with genuine hub molecules (HCN, H\u2082S, NH\u2083) and meaningful convergence points.\n- Issues: []\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Proline (racemic, DL-Proline)\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network constructs DL-Proline via the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic pathway of Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry), embedded within a broader prebiotic feedstock-generation framework spanning hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation, Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, atmospheric photochemistry, and surface cyanosulfidic chemistry. The core 5-step cyanosulfidic route builds the pyrrolidine ring unique to proline through cyanohydrin formation, H\u2082S-mediated thiolation-cyclization, Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis. Upstream hydrothermal reactions generate formaldehyde (via formate reduction), acetaldehyde (Fischer-Tropsch), and formamide, which feed into surface-environment aldol condensation, Michael addition, and formamide decomposition to supply the key starting materials HCN and 3-aminopropanal. Two independent HCN sources (formamide decomposition and atmospheric photochemistry) create convergent feedstock pathways. H\u2082S and NH\u2083 are catalytically recycled within the cyanosulfidic core. The product proline enters the prebiotic amino acid pool for peptide assembly in the biochemical environment. Note: the cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic proline; the origin of L-homochirality remains an open question.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-enal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acrolein\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O/c1-2-3-4/h2-3H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DL-Proline (racemic)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"Cu\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"copper\",\n      \"common_name\": \"elemental copper\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/Cu\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C7H12N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prolylglycine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pro-Gly dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C7H12N2O3/c1-3(10)9-5(7(11)12)2-4-6(9)8-5/h5-6,8H,1-4H2,(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. Molecular hydrogen dissociates on the iron-sulfide surface, generating surface-bound hydride. The hydride attacks the carbon of CO\u2082, reducing it to formate (HCOO\u207b). The alkaline pH favors formate stability.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is experimentally demonstrated under simulated hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015, Chemical Communications; Preiner et al., 2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution). This reaction is the first step in a Wood-Ljungdahl-like pathway on mineral surfaces and provides the C1 feedstock for downstream organic synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, rock-water interaction zone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on the magnetite/mackinawite surface by dissociated H\u2082. The two-electron reduction of formate proceeds through a surface-bound formyl intermediate, yielding formaldehyde (HCHO) and water. The reaction is thermodynamically driven by the high H\u2082 fugacity in serpentinization-derived fluids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Further reduction of formate to formaldehyde on iron-oxide/iron-sulfide surfaces has been proposed as part of the stepwise CO\u2082 reduction cascade in hydrothermal systems (He et al., 2019, PNAS; Muchowska et al., 2017, JACS). While yields are low compared to formate, the continuous H\u2082 flux in serpentinizing systems can drive the equilibrium. Formaldehyde is a critical C1 building block for downstream aldol and Strecker chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"black smoker vent conditions, high temperature zone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction on pyrite surfaces: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O. The FeS\u2082 surface provides the reducing power and catalytic sites for this well-known geochemical process at elevated temperatures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron sulfide minerals at hydrothermal temperatures is thermodynamically favorable and experimentally documented (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997, Science; Cody et al., 2000, Science). CO produced serves as a feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C2+ organics.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions on magnetite surface, subseafloor hydrothermal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) reactions on magnetite surfaces with H\u2082. CO is adsorbed and hydrogenated through surface methylene/methyl intermediates. Chain growth to C2 produces acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) as one of the oxygenated C2 products alongside methanol and ethanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis of C2 oxygenated organics including acetaldehyde on magnetite and other iron-oxide/iron-sulfide catalysts under hydrothermal conditions is experimentally demonstrated (McCollom et al., 1999, Origins of Life; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001, Origins of Life; Holm & Andersson, 2005). Acetaldehyde is a key building block for aldol condensation to longer-chain aldehydes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools, dehydration conditions concentrate reactants and drive condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate and ammonium ion are concentrated by evaporation in surface pools. Under dehydrating (dry phase) conditions on montmorillonite clay surfaces, amidation occurs: HCOO\u207b + NH\u2084\u207a \u2192 HCONH\u2082 + H\u2082O. The clay surface activates the carboxylate and provides a low-water microenvironment that drives the thermodynamically unfavorable condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide synthesis from ammonium formate under dehydrating conditions is a well-established prebiotic route (Saladino et al., 2012, Chemistry & Biodiversity; Botta et al., 2018, European Journal of Organic Chemistry). Montmorillonite clays catalyze this condensation by concentrating reactants in interlayer spaces and lowering the activation energy. Formamide is a key precursor for HCN and nucleobase synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermal/UV decomposition to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 280 nm), no ozone shield on early Earth; dry phase in geothermal fields\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide undergoes dehydration to HCN catalyzed by UV irradiation on TiO\u2082 photocatalytic surfaces. The UV photons excite TiO\u2082, generating reactive radical species that abstract the OH from formamide, or directly photolyze the C\u2013O bond, producing HCN and H\u2082O. Mineral surfaces (clays, metal oxides) further promote the decomposition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide decomposition to HCN on mineral surfaces including TiO\u2082 and montmorillonite is experimentally demonstrated (Saladino et al., 2001, Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry; Ferus et al., 2015, PNAS). UV-driven formamide chemistry is particularly efficient on anatase TiO\u2082, which is a common mineral on early Earth's surface. This provides a geochemically sourced HCN supply for cyanosulfidic chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric photochemical HCN synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (rutile/anatase)\", \"UV radiation\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photolysis (\u03bb < 200 nm)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Early Earth atmosphere with N\u2082 and CH\u2084 (or CO\u2082/N\u2082 with lightning); no ozone layer; HCN rains out into surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis of atmospheric N\u2082 and CH\u2084 (and/or CO\u2082) produces HCN through radical recombination. N\u2082 is dissociated by extreme UV into N atoms, which react with CH\u2083 and CH\u2082 radicals (from CH\u2084 photolysis) to form HCN. Lightning and impact-generated plasma also contribute. HCN dissolves in rainwater and accumulates in surface pools, particularly in cold traps or evaporitic settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Atmospheric photochemical production of HCN from N\u2082 and CH\u2084 (or N\u2082/CO\u2082) is a major prebiotic HCN source, extensively modeled and experimentally demonstrated (Zahnle, 1986, JGR; Tian et al., 2011, Earth and Planetary Science Letters; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019, Icarus). Estimated fluxes of 10\u2078-10\u2079 molecules cm\u207b\u00b2 s\u207b\u00b9 on the early Earth could sustain cyanosulfidic chemistry pools. TiO\u2082 mineral surfaces in the catchment area may assist photocatalytic activation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde to acrolein\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay), basic mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH (8-10), surface pool near geothermal source receiving hydrothermal outflow\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed aldol condensation followed by dehydration. The enolizable hydrogen of acetaldehyde is abstracted by basic mineral surfaces (clay, apatite), forming an enolate that attacks formaldehyde in a cross-aldol addition. The resulting \u03b2-hydroxyaldehyde (3-hydroxypropanal) spontaneously dehydrates under mild warming to yield acrolein (prop-2-enal, CH\u2082=CHCHO). Montmorillonite clay provides the basic catalytic sites and concentrates reactants through surface adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of small aldehydes on mineral surfaces is a well-established prebiotic transformation (Weber, 2001, Origins of Life; Orgel, 2004, Critical Reviews in Biochemistry; de Marcellus et al., 2015, PNAS). The specific cross-aldol of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde yielding acrolein is a textbook aldol-dehydration sequence favored by the greater electrophilicity of formaldehyde and the thermodynamic stability of the conjugated product. This provides the C3 \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde needed for Michael addition with ammonia.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein yielding 3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous surface pool with dissolved NH\u2083 from volcanic outgassing; mildly basic pH; clay surface catalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"1,4-Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to acrolein. The nitrogen lone pair of NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b2-carbon of acrolein (the Michael acceptor), forming a C\u2013N bond. Proton transfer yields 3-aminopropanal (NCCC=O). The reaction is kinetically facile in aqueous solution at ambient temperature. Montmorillonite clay concentrates both reactants through adsorption and may lower the activation barrier through surface acid-base catalysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein to produce 3-aminopropanal is the prebiotically plausible route to this key starting material identified by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). The reaction is a straightforward conjugate addition that proceeds readily in aqueous solution. Patel et al. note that 3-aminopropanal is a product of cyanosulfidic/surface chemistry from simple C1-C3 feedstocks. Montmorillonite catalysis of amine-aldehyde chemistry is well documented (Bujd\u00e1k & Rode, 1999, JME).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation (Step 1 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous nucleophilic addition)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions; mildly basic pH; HCN present from atmospheric/formamide sources\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, forming a new C\u2013C bond and yielding the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. The free primary amine group on the 3-aminopropanal chain is preserved for subsequent cyclization. This is a classic Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 1 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland, 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation from aminoaldehyde + HCN is well-established prebiotic chemistry. The product 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile contains both the amine and nitrile functional groups required for subsequent H\u2082S-mediated ring closure.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization (Step 2 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (H\u2082S-mediated)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic conditions; H\u2082S atmosphere or dissolved H\u2082S from volcanic/hydrothermal sources\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H\u2082S attacks the nitrile carbon of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, converting C\u2261N to a thioamide (C=S). The terminal primary amine then performs intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the thioamide carbon, closing the five-membered pyrrolidine ring with release of NH\u2083. This one-pot thiolation-cyclization simultaneously achieves ring closure and introduces the thione functional group central to subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 2 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The H\u2082S-mediated activation of nitriles toward cyclization is a hallmark of the Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework. The intramolecular distance between the amine and thioamide in this substrate is exactly right for five-membered ring formation, explaining the selectivity for the pyrrolidine ring of proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation (Step 3 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"native copper (Cu\u2070)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu\u2070) with H\u2082S as co-reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic surface pool; native copper deposits formed by Cu\u00b2\u207a reduction by H\u2082S in sulfide-rich surface settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive removal of the C3 hydroxyl group from 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione. The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system donates electrons to cleave the C\u2013OH bond: Cu\u2070 is oxidized (Cu\u2070 \u2192 Cu\u207a/Cu\u00b2\u207a) while H\u2082S provides additional reducing equivalents and protons. The product is the fully reduced pyrrolidine-2-thione with loss of water. The thione group at C2 is retained.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 3 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system is a prebiotically plausible reductant \u2014 native copper deposits form when dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions are reduced by H\u2082S in geochemical settings. Patel et al. explicitly use elemental copper and H\u2082S as co-reductants for this transformation. The steady-state availability of Cu\u2070 in prebiotic surface environments remains an open question (see Open Questions).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Thione-to-nitrile exchange with HCN (Step 4 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (HCN-mediated displacement)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic conditions; HCN present; released H\u2082S is recycled into Step 2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide displaces the thione sulfur at C2 of the pyrrolidine ring. HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic thioamide carbon. The C=S bond is cleaved with release of H\u2082S, and a new C\u2013CN bond is formed, yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This thione-to-nitrile exchange is a key interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry, converting sulfur-containing functional groups to nitrogen-containing ones. The released H\u2082S is available for recycling into the thiolation-cyclization step (rxn_011).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 4 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The thione-to-nitrile exchange exemplifies the elegant sulfur cycling in cyanosulfidic chemistry: H\u2082S consumed in Step 2 (rxn_011) is regenerated here, creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. This HCN-driven displacement is thermodynamically favorable because the C\u2261N triple bond is more stable than the C=S double bond in the product context.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to proline (Step 5 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals and clay surfaces may catalyze hydrolysis; metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) accelerate nitrile hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"2 equivalents of H\u2082O consumed; proceeds through pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide intermediate; timescale of days to weeks at ambient temperature and neutral pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential hydrolysis of the nitrile group of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Water attacks the nitrile carbon nucleophilically, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide). The amide undergoes a second hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed overall. The product is racemic proline (DL-proline). Metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) present in surface pools and phosphate/clay mineral surfaces may catalyze the hydrolysis and accelerate the rate-limiting step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 5 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). Nitrile hydrolysis is the final step completing the conversion from aminonitrile to amino acid. At ambient temperature and neutral pH, this step may be slow (days to weeks), constituting a potential kinetic bottleneck. However, the presence of dissolved metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a) and mineral surfaces can significantly accelerate nitrile hydrolysis (Baxter et al., 2009, JOC). The pathway produces racemic proline; the origin of L-homochirality remains unresolved.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Proline-containing peptide formation via wet-dry cycling\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay) surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools; dehydration drives peptide bond condensation; repeated cycles increase oligopeptide length\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Proline and glycine are concentrated by evaporation on montmorillonite clay surfaces. During the dry (dehydrating) phase, the amino group of glycine attacks the activated carboxyl group of proline (or vice versa), forming a peptide bond with loss of water. Montmorillonite catalyzes the condensation by adsorbing amino acids in an orientation favorable for peptide bond formation. The cyclic pyrrolidine structure of proline introduces conformational rigidity (kinks and turns) into the resulting peptides, which may have functional significance in early protometabolism.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Peptide bond formation via wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces is a well-established prebiotic polymerization mechanism (Lahav et al., 1978, Science; Rode, 1999, Peptides; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2020, Chemical Reviews). Montmorillonite has been shown to catalyze the formation of peptides up to 50+ residues (Ferris et al., 1996, Nature). Proline-containing peptides are of particular interest because proline's rigid pyrrolidine ring constrains polypeptide backbone geometry, potentially generating early catalytic structures. Glycine is used as the co-reactant as it is the most abundant prebiotic amino acid (Miller, 1953).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal-to-surface cyanosulfidic proline synthesis (formamide-derived HCN)\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete route from CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents through formate \u2192 formamide \u2192 HCN in surface pools, combined with formaldehyde + acetaldehyde \u2192 acrolein \u2192 3-aminopropanal, converging in the 5-step cyanosulfidic proline pathway. HCN from formamide decomposition drives both the cyanohydrin step and the thione-to-nitrile exchange.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN route to proline via cyanosulfidic core\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric photochemical HCN (from N\u2082 + CH\u2084 + UV) supplies the cyanide for both the cyanohydrin formation and thione-to-nitrile exchange steps of the cyanosulfidic proline pathway. 3-Aminopropanal is produced via the hydrothermal formaldehyde + acetaldehyde \u2192 acrolein \u2192 Michael addition route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide HCN branch for cyanohydrin step\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN derived from the hydrothermal formate \u2192 surface formamide \u2192 HCN route feeds specifically into the cyanohydrin formation step (rxn_010), extending the 3-aminopropanal carbon chain to form 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. This is the carbon-nitrogen bond-forming step that sets up the C4 chain for pyrrolidine ring closure.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Core cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015)\",\n      \"description\": \"The experimentally validated 5-step cyanosulfidic pathway from 3-aminopropanal and HCN to proline: (1) cyanohydrin formation, (2) H\u2082S thiolation-cyclization, (3) Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation, (4) thione-to-nitrile exchange, (5) nitrile hydrolysis. This is the core of the network, constructing the pyrrolidine ring unique to proline through sulfur-mediated ring closure.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN branch for thione-to-nitrile exchange\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric photochemical HCN feeds specifically into the thione-to-nitrile exchange step (rxn_013), replacing the thione sulfur on pyrrolidine-2-thione with a nitrile group and regenerating H\u2082S for the sulfur cycle. This provides an independent HCN source for the final ring-modification steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"H\u2082S catalytic sulfur cycle\",\n      \"description\": \"Catalytic recycling of H\u2082S within the cyanosulfidic core: H\u2082S is consumed in the thiolation-cyclization step (rxn_011) and in the Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation (rxn_012), then regenerated by thione-to-nitrile exchange (rxn_013). This elegant sulfur cycle means that sub-stoichiometric H\u2082S can drive the overall transformation, with the sulfur serving as a catalytic shuttle between thioamide and nitrile functional groups.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"NH\u2083 nitrogen recycling pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia is consumed upstream in formamide synthesis (rxn_005) and Michael addition to acrolein (rxn_009), and is regenerated by the thiolation-cyclization (rxn_011, which releases NH\u2083 during ring closure) and the final nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_014). This nitrogen economy means NH\u2083 functions as both a substrate and a recycled product, sustaining the network with sub-stoichiometric external nitrogen input.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082-to-formaldehyde feedstock route\",\n      \"description\": \"Two-step hydrothermal reduction of CO\u2082 to formaldehyde via formate intermediate on greigite and magnetite mineral surfaces. Formaldehyde exits the hydrothermal system to surface pools where it serves as a C1 building block for acrolein synthesis via aldol condensation with acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch acetaldehyde route to 3-aminopropanal\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO by the reverse water-gas shift on pyrite (rxn_003), then CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite to produce acetaldehyde (rxn_004). Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools where it reacts with hydrothermal-derived formaldehyde in aldol condensation to form acrolein, which undergoes Michael addition with NH\u2083 to yield 3-aminopropanal, the starting substrate for the cyanosulfidic core.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Proline to peptide assembly in biochemical environment\",\n      \"description\": \"Proline produced by the cyanosulfidic pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool and is incorporated into peptides via wet-dry cycling on montmorillonite clay surfaces. The rigid pyrrolidine ring of proline introduces conformational constraints (kinks, turns) into peptides, potentially generating early catalytic or structural motifs. This pathway connects surface cyanosulfidic chemistry to the biochemical assembly of macromolecules.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide (HCN) \u2014 converges from two independent production routes (formamide decomposition and atmospheric photochemistry) and distributes to two consumption points (cyanohydrin formation and thione-to-nitrile exchange)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia (NH\u2083) \u2014 consumed in formamide synthesis and Michael addition to acrolein; regenerated in thiolation-cyclization and nitrile hydrolysis, creating a catalytic nitrogen cycle\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S) \u2014 consumed in thiolation-cyclization and reductive deoxygenation; regenerated by thione-to-nitrile exchange, creating the catalytic sulfur cycle central to cyanosulfidic chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate \u2014 produced by hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction on greigite; consumed by both formaldehyde synthesis (further reduction) and formamide synthesis (amidation with NH\u2083), branching the network into two downstream routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Proline (racemic, DL-Proline)", "overall_strategy": "The network constructs DL-Proline via the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic pathway of Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry), embedded within a broader prebiotic feedstock-generation framework spanning hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation, Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, atmospheric photochemistry, and surface cyanosulfidic chemistry. The core 5-step cyanosulfidic route builds the pyrrolidine ring unique to proline through cyanohydrin formation, H\u2082S-mediated thiolation-cyclization, Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation, thione-to-nitrile exchange, and nitrile hydrolysis. Upstream hydrothermal reactions generate formaldehyde (via formate reduction), acetaldehyde (Fischer-Tropsch), and formamide, which feed into surface-environment aldol condensation, Michael addition, and formamide decomposition to supply the key starting materials HCN and 3-aminopropanal. Two independent HCN sources (formamide decomposition and atmospheric photochemistry) create convergent feedstock pathways. H\u2082S and NH\u2083 are catalytically recycled within the cyanosulfidic core. The product proline enters the prebiotic amino acid pool for peptide assembly in the biochemical environment. Note: the cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic proline; the origin of L-homochirality remains an open question.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H4O", "iupac_name": "prop-2-enal", "common_name": "acrolein", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O/c1-2-3-4/h2-3H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanal", "common_name": "3-aminopropanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h3H,1-2,4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c5-2-1-4(7)3-6/h4,7H,1-2,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H7NOS", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "common_name": "3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NOS/c6-3-1-2-5-4(3)7/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,5,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H7NS", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-thione", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-thione", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NS/c6-4-2-1-3-5-4/h1-3H2,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "DL-Proline (racemic)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "Cu", "iupac_name": "copper", "common_name": "elemental copper", "inchi": "InChI=1S/Cu", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "glycine", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C7H12N2O3", "iupac_name": "prolylglycine", "common_name": "Pro-Gly dipeptide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C7H12N2O3/c1-3(10)9-5(7(11)12)2-4-6(9)8-5/h5-6,8H,1-4H2,(H,11,12)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. Molecular hydrogen dissociates on the iron-sulfide surface, generating surface-bound hydride. The hydride attacks the carbon of CO\u2082, reducing it to formate (HCOO\u207b). The alkaline pH favors formate stability.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is experimentally demonstrated under simulated hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015, Chemical Communications; Preiner et al., 2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution). This reaction is the first step in a Wood-Ljungdahl-like pathway on mineral surfaces and provides the C1 feedstock for downstream organic synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-450K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, rock-water interaction zone"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on the magnetite/mackinawite surface by dissociated H\u2082. The two-electron reduction of formate proceeds through a surface-bound formyl intermediate, yielding formaldehyde (HCHO) and water. The reaction is thermodynamically driven by the high H\u2082 fugacity in serpentinization-derived fluids.", "reasoning": "Further reduction of formate to formaldehyde on iron-oxide/iron-sulfide surfaces has been proposed as part of the stepwise CO\u2082 reduction cascade in hydrothermal systems (He et al., 2019, PNAS; Muchowska et al., 2017, JACS). While yields are low compared to formate, the continuous H\u2082 flux in serpentinizing systems can drive the equilibrium. Formaldehyde is a critical C1 building block for downstream aldol and Strecker chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "black smoker vent conditions, high temperature zone"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction on pyrite surfaces: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O. The FeS\u2082 surface provides the reducing power and catalytic sites for this well-known geochemical process at elevated temperatures.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron sulfide minerals at hydrothermal temperatures is thermodynamically favorable and experimentally documented (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997, Science; Cody et al., 2000, Science). CO produced serves as a feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of C2+ organics."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions on magnetite surface, subseafloor hydrothermal"}, "mechanism": "CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) reactions on magnetite surfaces with H\u2082. CO is adsorbed and hydrogenated through surface methylene/methyl intermediates. Chain growth to C2 produces acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) as one of the oxygenated C2 products alongside methanol and ethanol.", "reasoning": "FTT synthesis of C2 oxygenated organics including acetaldehyde on magnetite and other iron-oxide/iron-sulfide catalysts under hydrothermal conditions is experimentally demonstrated (McCollom et al., 1999, Origins of Life; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001, Origins of Life; Holm & Andersson, 2005). Acetaldehyde is a key building block for aldol condensation to longer-chain aldehydes."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools, dehydration conditions concentrate reactants and drive condensation"}, "mechanism": "Formate and ammonium ion are concentrated by evaporation in surface pools. Under dehydrating (dry phase) conditions on montmorillonite clay surfaces, amidation occurs: HCOO\u207b + NH\u2084\u207a \u2192 HCONH\u2082 + H\u2082O. The clay surface activates the carboxylate and provides a low-water microenvironment that drives the thermodynamically unfavorable condensation.", "reasoning": "Formamide synthesis from ammonium formate under dehydrating conditions is a well-established prebiotic route (Saladino et al., 2012, Chemistry & Biodiversity; Botta et al., 2018, European Journal of Organic Chemistry). Montmorillonite clays catalyze this condensation by concentrating reactants in interlayer spaces and lowering the activation energy. Formamide is a key precursor for HCN and nucleobase synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formamide thermal/UV decomposition to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 280 nm), no ozone shield on early Earth; dry phase in geothermal fields"}, "mechanism": "Formamide undergoes dehydration to HCN catalyzed by UV irradiation on TiO\u2082 photocatalytic surfaces. The UV photons excite TiO\u2082, generating reactive radical species that abstract the OH from formamide, or directly photolyze the C\u2013O bond, producing HCN and H\u2082O. Mineral surfaces (clays, metal oxides) further promote the decomposition.", "reasoning": "Formamide decomposition to HCN on mineral surfaces including TiO\u2082 and montmorillonite is experimentally demonstrated (Saladino et al., 2001, Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry; Ferus et al., 2015, PNAS). UV-driven formamide chemistry is particularly efficient on anatase TiO\u2082, which is a common mineral on early Earth's surface. This provides a geochemically sourced HCN supply for cyanosulfidic chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Atmospheric photochemical HCN synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (rutile/anatase)", "UV radiation"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photolysis (\u03bb < 200 nm)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Early Earth atmosphere with N\u2082 and CH\u2084 (or CO\u2082/N\u2082 with lightning); no ozone layer; HCN rains out into surface pools"}, "mechanism": "UV photolysis of atmospheric N\u2082 and CH\u2084 (and/or CO\u2082) produces HCN through radical recombination. N\u2082 is dissociated by extreme UV into N atoms, which react with CH\u2083 and CH\u2082 radicals (from CH\u2084 photolysis) to form HCN. Lightning and impact-generated plasma also contribute. HCN dissolves in rainwater and accumulates in surface pools, particularly in cold traps or evaporitic settings.", "reasoning": "Atmospheric photochemical production of HCN from N\u2082 and CH\u2084 (or N\u2082/CO\u2082) is a major prebiotic HCN source, extensively modeled and experimentally demonstrated (Zahnle, 1986, JGR; Tian et al., 2011, Earth and Planetary Science Letters; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019, Icarus). Estimated fluxes of 10\u2078-10\u2079 molecules cm\u207b\u00b2 s\u207b\u00b9 on the early Earth could sustain cyanosulfidic chemistry pools. TiO\u2082 mineral surfaces in the catchment area may assist photocatalytic activation."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde to acrolein", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay), basic mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline pH (8-10), surface pool near geothermal source receiving hydrothermal outflow"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed aldol condensation followed by dehydration. The enolizable hydrogen of acetaldehyde is abstracted by basic mineral surfaces (clay, apatite), forming an enolate that attacks formaldehyde in a cross-aldol addition. The resulting \u03b2-hydroxyaldehyde (3-hydroxypropanal) spontaneously dehydrates under mild warming to yield acrolein (prop-2-enal, CH\u2082=CHCHO). Montmorillonite clay provides the basic catalytic sites and concentrates reactants through surface adsorption.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of small aldehydes on mineral surfaces is a well-established prebiotic transformation (Weber, 2001, Origins of Life; Orgel, 2004, Critical Reviews in Biochemistry; de Marcellus et al., 2015, PNAS). The specific cross-aldol of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde yielding acrolein is a textbook aldol-dehydration sequence favored by the greater electrophilicity of formaldehyde and the thermodynamic stability of the conjugated product. This provides the C3 \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde needed for Michael addition with ammonia."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein yielding 3-aminopropanal", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous surface pool with dissolved NH\u2083 from volcanic outgassing; mildly basic pH; clay surface catalysis"}, "mechanism": "1,4-Conjugate (Michael) addition of ammonia to acrolein. The nitrogen lone pair of NH\u2083 attacks the \u03b2-carbon of acrolein (the Michael acceptor), forming a C\u2013N bond. Proton transfer yields 3-aminopropanal (NCCC=O). The reaction is kinetically facile in aqueous solution at ambient temperature. Montmorillonite clay concentrates both reactants through adsorption and may lower the activation barrier through surface acid-base catalysis.", "reasoning": "The Michael addition of ammonia to acrolein to produce 3-aminopropanal is the prebiotically plausible route to this key starting material identified by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). The reaction is a straightforward conjugate addition that proceeds readily in aqueous solution. Patel et al. note that 3-aminopropanal is a product of cyanosulfidic/surface chemistry from simple C1-C3 feedstocks. Montmorillonite catalysis of amine-aldehyde chemistry is well documented (Bujd\u00e1k & Rode, 1999, JME)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation (Step 1 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous nucleophilic addition)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions; mildly basic pH; HCN present from atmospheric/formamide sources"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl of 3-aminopropanal. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, forming a new C\u2013C bond and yielding the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile (cyanohydrin) 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile. The free primary amine group on the 3-aminopropanal chain is preserved for subsequent cyclization. This is a classic Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation step.", "reasoning": "This is Step 1 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland, 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The Strecker-type cyanohydrin formation from aminoaldehyde + HCN is well-established prebiotic chemistry. The product 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile contains both the amine and nitrile functional groups required for subsequent H\u2082S-mediated ring closure."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "H\u2082S-mediated thiolation and intramolecular cyclization (Step 2 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (H\u2082S-mediated)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic conditions; H\u2082S atmosphere or dissolved H\u2082S from volcanic/hydrothermal sources"}, "mechanism": "H\u2082S attacks the nitrile carbon of 4-amino-2-hydroxybutanenitrile, converting C\u2261N to a thioamide (C=S). The terminal primary amine then performs intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the thioamide carbon, closing the five-membered pyrrolidine ring with release of NH\u2083. This one-pot thiolation-cyclization simultaneously achieves ring closure and introduces the thione functional group central to subsequent cyanosulfidic transformations.", "reasoning": "This is Step 2 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The H\u2082S-mediated activation of nitriles toward cyclization is a hallmark of the Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework. The intramolecular distance between the amine and thioamide in this substrate is exactly right for five-membered ring formation, explaining the selectivity for the pyrrolidine ring of proline."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cu/H\u2082S reductive deoxygenation (Step 3 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_021", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["native copper (Cu\u2070)", "hydrogen sulfide (H\u2082S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu\u2070) with H\u2082S as co-reductant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pool; native copper deposits formed by Cu\u00b2\u207a reduction by H\u2082S in sulfide-rich surface settings"}, "mechanism": "Reductive removal of the C3 hydroxyl group from 3-hydroxypyrrolidine-2-thione. The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system donates electrons to cleave the C\u2013OH bond: Cu\u2070 is oxidized (Cu\u2070 \u2192 Cu\u207a/Cu\u00b2\u207a) while H\u2082S provides additional reducing equivalents and protons. The product is the fully reduced pyrrolidine-2-thione with loss of water. The thione group at C2 is retained.", "reasoning": "This is Step 3 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The Cu/H\u2082S reducing system is a prebiotically plausible reductant \u2014 native copper deposits form when dissolved Cu\u00b2\u207a ions are reduced by H\u2082S in geochemical settings. Patel et al. explicitly use elemental copper and H\u2082S as co-reductants for this transformation. The steady-state availability of Cu\u2070 in prebiotic surface environments remains an open question (see Open Questions)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Thione-to-nitrile exchange with HCN (Step 4 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (HCN-mediated displacement)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic conditions; HCN present; released H\u2082S is recycled into Step 2"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide displaces the thione sulfur at C2 of the pyrrolidine ring. HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic thioamide carbon. The C=S bond is cleaved with release of H\u2082S, and a new C\u2013CN bond is formed, yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This thione-to-nitrile exchange is a key interconversion in cyanosulfidic chemistry, converting sulfur-containing functional groups to nitrogen-containing ones. The released H\u2082S is available for recycling into the thiolation-cyclization step (rxn_011).", "reasoning": "This is Step 4 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). The thione-to-nitrile exchange exemplifies the elegant sulfur cycling in cyanosulfidic chemistry: H\u2082S consumed in Step 2 (rxn_011) is regenerated here, creating a catalytic sulfur cycle. This HCN-driven displacement is thermodynamically favorable because the C\u2261N triple bond is more stable than the C=S double bond in the product context."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis to proline (Step 5 of cyanosulfidic proline pathway)", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals and clay surfaces may catalyze hydrolysis; metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) accelerate nitrile hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "2 equivalents of H\u2082O consumed; proceeds through pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide intermediate; timescale of days to weeks at ambient temperature and neutral pH"}, "mechanism": "Sequential hydrolysis of the nitrile group of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Water attacks the nitrile carbon nucleophilically, forming a primary amide intermediate (pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide). The amide undergoes a second hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. Two equivalents of water are consumed overall. The product is racemic proline (DL-proline). Metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) present in surface pools and phosphate/clay mineral surfaces may catalyze the hydrolysis and accelerate the rate-limiting step.", "reasoning": "This is Step 5 of the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic proline pathway (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202). Nitrile hydrolysis is the final step completing the conversion from aminonitrile to amino acid. At ambient temperature and neutral pH, this step may be slow (days to weeks), constituting a potential kinetic bottleneck. However, the presence of dissolved metal ions (Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a) and mineral surfaces can significantly accelerate nitrile hydrolysis (Baxter et al., 2009, JOC). The pathway produces racemic proline; the origin of L-homochirality remains unresolved."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Proline-containing peptide formation via wet-dry cycling", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_023", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay) surface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools; dehydration drives peptide bond condensation; repeated cycles increase oligopeptide length"}, "mechanism": "Proline and glycine are concentrated by evaporation on montmorillonite clay surfaces. During the dry (dehydrating) phase, the amino group of glycine attacks the activated carboxyl group of proline (or vice versa), forming a peptide bond with loss of water. Montmorillonite catalyzes the condensation by adsorbing amino acids in an orientation favorable for peptide bond formation. The cyclic pyrrolidine structure of proline introduces conformational rigidity (kinks and turns) into the resulting peptides, which may have functional significance in early protometabolism.", "reasoning": "Peptide bond formation via wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces is a well-established prebiotic polymerization mechanism (Lahav et al., 1978, Science; Rode, 1999, Peptides; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2020, Chemical Reviews). Montmorillonite has been shown to catalyze the formation of peptides up to 50+ residues (Ferris et al., 1996, Nature). Proline-containing peptides are of particular interest because proline's rigid pyrrolidine ring constrains polypeptide backbone geometry, potentially generating early catalytic structures. Glycine is used as the co-reactant as it is the most abundant prebiotic amino acid (Miller, 1953)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full hydrothermal-to-surface cyanosulfidic proline synthesis (formamide-derived HCN)", "description": "Complete route from CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents through formate \u2192 formamide \u2192 HCN in surface pools, combined with formaldehyde + ac